Chris, I'm not sure about that one. We haven't use this pattern yet in our modules where the XXX::init class is included in an other class requiring it.

I have 2 suggestions:
- Add a dependency on the class itself instead so user is forced to include it beforehand.
- Remove the check: other plugins aren't doing such validation like the one introduced in ML2."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-12-29 11:22:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'll defer to your judgment on this one. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 7888, 'date': '2014-01-01 15:35:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Only add a dependency is not working, since it is not a question sqequence but of context.
I thin there are the following 3 solutions:
1.) proposed include
2.) remove test
3.) an inherit of the upper class is probably also working

I favor 2, since it reduces complexity.'}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2014-01-08 22:21:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 7888, 'date': '2014-01-16 07:59:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Restored

This is still not working.
How do we decide ?'}, {'account_id': 6994, 'date': '2014-01-16 08:29:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The default for core_plugin in the neutron class is ovs, not ML2, so in the event of a user not instantiating the neutron class explicitly, including it with its defaults when the user is trying to use ML2 will result in the ML2 class setting its config, and then not being used. I think this would be very confusing behavior, and I am therefore against this change.

I'd be happier with checking to see if the neutron class is included in the catalogue and failing if it's not there, and the corresponding change for other modules."}, {'account_id': 7888, 'date': '2014-01-16 08:36:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-16 08:42:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Remove check for correct core_plugin when using ml2.

This checks fails, because $::neutron::core_plugin
is not available in the context of ml2.pp.

Change-Id: I96c11c5a57c530f72e0e71447831b8219c12a685

Add Python3 deprecated assert* to HACKING.rst

When we added H234 and H235 to check for deprecated asserts in Python
3.x (assert(Not)Equals, assert_), we forgot to add them to HACKING.rst

Change-Id: Id91977d76935998f5e5ae19dc089ee46d013aacb

commit_message:
Re-Add section on assertRaises(Exception

When hacking was originally part of nova, there was a section on
assertRaises but this was moved out of HACKING, and into
nova/tests/README.rst in nova change
I0e660b6c2a77c5613c5a523ba0a64c3d7f6dd128

Since hacking has been enforcing this rule, H202, from the beginning,
add this section back into HACKING.rst

Change-Id: Ia7e0c3f908136c75333cb66ff90c7990c80027be

commit_message:
Cleanup HACKING.rst

* remove two rules covered by pep8 since we already say 'see pep8' and
  gate on them via the pep8 tool:
* use code notation where appropriate
* fix formatting around apache2 header rule
* update import exceptions block, to match DEFAULT_IMPORT_EXCEPTIONS

Change-Id: I3febff29694865948c309340a20820c020e43d15

HACKING.rst, except for hacking itself.  Keep the hacking guide as the

commit_message:
Add 'api_workers' option to support multiple api services

Use the WSGI code from service.py to create multiple workers
processes to handle API load. Add 'api_workers' option to
config the number of api workers to start.

DocImpact

Implements blueprint multi-workers-for-api-server

Change-Id: I2f2033af7cb01c8c87f7f06d5c562065753550ed

I filed a bug against the python bindings: https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-keystoneclient/+bug/1263069'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-12-20 13:01:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I know it'll put be in a bad angle but ... I personally have two problems with this:

  1. why shall we circumvent the  rate limits? Isn't that going against the very purpose of the limits? Why not just drop the limits (or configure apprpriately) then?

  2. when limit is hit the server is supposed to return a "Retry-After", maybe we can implement something around that?'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-12-20 13:05:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2013-12-20 13:23:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks Giulio, that's a good point, I should honor the "Retry-after" header (if available). I will implement the change.

The idea is not to circumvent the rate-limit, but to retry when appropriate. Removing the limit or decrease them would ignore the very purpose of having the limits in place which is to protect the system from overload.

Besides, when running tempest against real clouds (rather than disposable ones), meddling with the rate limits may not always be possible.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-12-20 13:32:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: No score

I see (and agree with) your point about using tempest against a "live" deployment, thanks. I'm removing the -1.'}, {'account_id': 5174, 'date': '2013-12-27 13:35:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think we also need to handle the swift scenario added couple of days ago."}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-01-03 09:38:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Will do that, thanks Mauro.'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-01-03 10:56:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

To handle the Retry-After header I would have to start looking into the what the request method returns, which is different for each client. I would prefer to keep the static value for now, and have Retry-After as a further improvement if required.
Regarding swiftclient, it already provides retry mechanism, so there's no need for monkey-patching it. I just passed the configured retry# and retry delay parameter into swift client, so that it behaves like other clients."}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-01-03 11:02:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-03 11:52:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Implements official clients with retry

Add function to monkey patched official clients to handle
retries on rate limiting errors.
Each client has an http client within, with something like
a request method. The request method is replaced with a new
request_with_retry, function of the original method.
For Swift using the existing retry functionality.

Also fixes self.config -> CONF

Closes-bug: #1250809
Closes-bug: #1187737

commit_message:
Grant group member to has write access on the secret key store path

The httpd subprocess is running by apache user who is under apache
group, we need save the secret key store file into a path which apache
user has write access.

Close-bug: #1267691

Change-Id: Ia7effc95d62404c2b2901273909d69871c2d6899

commit_message:
move datastore manager to the datastore version

This moves the datastore manager field to the datastore version object
so that we can have managers per datastore version and they can be
shared if nessesary.

implements blueprint move-manager-to-datastore-version

commit_message:
datastore manager moved to datastore version

Moving the manager from the datastore object to the datastore version
object to allow managers to be changed per version and this change is
reflected in the calls made to trove-manage to update the datastore and
datastore version.

paritally implements bp move-manager-to-datastore-version

Change-Id: I3c720153cbb08a8a3278debc3936854209576241

commit_message:
remove references and uses of fixed_range wrt nova.conf

Fixes: bug #1269876

As per commit https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/1f6c4f5,
fixed_range in nova.conf is deprecated.  We don't need to be setting it
any more.

Change-Id: Ie9371a54c3bcbad3c45b851b67f78c38c43940bf

commit_message:
Bugfix ring_script.rb output parser

This bugfix allows ring_script.rb to handler later versions
of swift-ring-builder that could be required in upgrade or
downgrade scenerios in the stable/grizzly branch.

Change-Id: I1fffddcf290fd077220021dd54df7f29ddfd7a8a
Partial-Bug: #1266922

commit_message:
Add possibility to create Failure from exception

In some cases it's great to have possibility to create
misc.Failure object from an exception directly. This
commit adds the 'from_exception' class method to create
misc.Failure in such way.

Change-Id: I44ae6720196b7bbe1e4ad538018487f0761a1af5

'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-12-03 07:23:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The use case is not really clear to me. Do you have a real example where this new function is used, I mean other than the test case?

In addition, I think we should also change the hot template guide and hot spec when introducing new functions. I could help with that when I understand the backgrounds better.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-12-06 11:07:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> The use case is not really clear to me. Do you have a real example where this new function is used, I mean other than the test case?

The use-case is to format chunks of data into a mime-multi-part message for cloud-init, because that is the way cloud-init allows you to pass multiple files in one chunk of userdata.  

This allows you to e.g specify a cloud-config "file" or section, and also other sections (boothook, script, handler for custom mime-type like x-cfntools)

So we should be able to use this to create a better and more flexible interface to cloud-init via heat templates, when using the RAW user_data_format (as opposed to relying on cfntools)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-12-06 11:11:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Looks good, but question re abuse via CFN templates."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-12-06 12:01:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Steven: ok, so technically I understand the use case, but I have a concern with exposing this as an intrinsic function as part of HOT. For me this brings low-level programming logic into the templat format that should allow for some level of abstraction.

If there was a resource type that implemented really specific behavior of passing data around, fine, but having this as a general function in HOT just feels bad to me.

See also my comment in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59555'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-12-06 21:44:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Some minor defensive programming concerns and I share shary's question around CFN template issues, but otherwise LGTM.

@Thomas I disagree that this is too functional. In my mind its no different than str_replace. It really does make template authoring easier and prevents us from writing resources that don't actually create or manage anything. Besides an equivalent resource would wind up looking very similar in practice."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-12-08 22:00:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

commit_message:
Move to use "get_password" instead of "{user,service,db}_password"

The user_password, service_password and db_password functions are redundant
since they simply call "secret". Creates a get_password function that will
accept a "type" of db, service or user.

All instances of these calls have been changed to call get_password

Change-Id: Ic73c99034638ec092192d11e37671edbba0e48ef
Partial-Bug: #1195915

commit_message:
Refactoring local and scalable engines

* Moved iethods start_workflow_execution and convey_task_result into
 abstract engine
* Refactored existing local engine unit tests
* Added simple unit tests for scalable engine
* Minor cosmetic changes (imports, blank lines)

Change-Id: Ic781b134068f52ed5827b945fb57b202239fe9c4

Set default for USE_CACHE

This is usually set by devtest.sh but may not always be present, e.g. if
devtest_ramdisk.sh is called from toci or standalone.

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-01-13 03:34:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

When I looked closely this patch exposed some misunderstandings about how the infra -> toci glue works.

Infra will have a Jenkins slave node that has toci checked out on it, and will run toci_gate.sh directly from jenkins. *any* changes we want to make to how it's invoked get done in ./modules/openstack_project/files/jenkins_job_builder/config/tripleo.yaml in the infra/config tree.

So, I've refactored this patch to call the broker client from within toci_gate, which is how the handoff should happen. We need to teach infra how to supply the broker IP address to us - probably that just involves someone with the infra cloud credentials creating a floating IP for the broker in the tripleo-cd-cloud, and then we can put that IP address in the JJB definition.

The devtest calls depend on the (large) stack of refactoring to devtest to be toci friendly, but since this doesn't affect toci in Dan's environment, we should be able to land the patch here and use manual testing to iterate."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-01-13 06:26:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

commit_message:
Update toci_gate_test.sh to use the broker.

toci_gate_test now enters the broker and chains into toci_devtest.sh
via test-envclient. Under the hood this is doing:

$ testenv-client -b <geardserver>:4730 -- ./toci_devtest.sh

This depends on both a gearman broker and at least one registered
test env being deployed.

toci_devtest includes the code to apply the broker supplied SSH key to
the system and then attempts to run the first few stages of devtest,
preserving the test environment definintion from the broker.

The astute of eye may observe that we haven't solved how to pass the gear
server host into the test environment yet... that may require an
openstack-infra/config patch.

Change-Id: I53ce4ca687283a924ea055267ea90f20d6632651
Co-Authored-By: Robert Collins <rbtcollins@hp.com>

commit_message:
Only add ceilometer user to nova group if using compute agent

When using ceilometer outside of the compute context (ex: with the
swift middleware), puppet-ceilometer attempts to add the user to
the nova group which does not (and probably should not) exist on
the swift nodes.

Change-Id: I6cc68152325a967c024ce611f92a90ce0afba8cc
(cherry picked from commit d064997cd4c50d9b5365fe2ffca60e14a86b08e1)

Fix pep error "E121"/"E126"

Currently, "run_tests.sh -p " reported E126, E121, E122 and E128 as
pep error.

This patch fixes E121 and E126.

commit_message:
Add Tripleo CI user.

This will permit Tripleo CI to obtain IPs from neutron in
ci-overcloud.tripleo.org(the ci overcloud). Once merged the user will
need to be added manually to the ci-overcloud, this should eventually be
automated and persisted when we move to the cd-overcloud.

Change-Id: I9c312fdc71895544ed34bfe4c3abf6aa5a2ea4ef

commit_message:
Add a db check for CHARSET=utf8

This is to prevent confusing migration errors caused by
tables having mixed character sets like latin1.

Change-Id: I19da8d5e2d972c78d0f9fb4325445f538ed35600
Closes-bug: #1261605

commit_message:
Use entry points to discover options in libraries

When generating the sample configuration file, we want to include
options defined in libraries used by the application (especially
oslo libraries). Add a section to the sample generator to look
at entry points in the 'oslo.config.opts' namespace and include
their return values in the output.

Implements: blueprint improve-config-discovery-for-docs
Related-Bug: #1241566

Change-Id: I635cd8e60ca687851c9dd891667ecc2ca3e8720c

commit_message:
Move to use "get_password" instead of "{user,service,db}_password"

The user_password, service_password and db_password functions are redundant
since they simply call "secret". Creates a get_password function that will
accept a "type" of db, service or user.

All instances of these calls have been changed to call get_password

Change-Id: Ifdb5c7b3f590431aaa7ffc021cdee34899ac8c15
Partial-Bug: #1195915

commit_message:
Enable setting up translation handler via CONF

Just like with other log settings, enable setting up the
TranslationHandler via a CONF option, outside the logging.conf
file. The patch adds a new CONF option called 'log_additional_locale'.

Change-Id: I71e0a564e13b782d741a4e5eafe30bf82569a02c

commit_message:
Sync gettextutils from Oslo

The Message class in Oslo, in charge of providing delayed translation
features, was improved and a new feature was implemented to enable
creation of addition logs in different locales.

Latest Oslo commit:
221c37d Allow the Message class to have non-English default locales

bp i18n-messages

Change-Id: I9ac8a0da9ea3b7b393f81c255332d83bbcab1da9

commit_message:
lockutils: remove local usage

This doesn't seem like it's used by anything any more, so let's just
remove this local usage altogether. This also drops the lock check from
RPC, which shouldn't be a problem considering that this library is
already deprecated altogether.

Change-Id: I87ff0338adcfa092fd21acad5cf41d5746be1efe

Falcon 0.1.8 returns lowercased headers to the client. This *should* be

commit_message:
test: Use srmock header_dict in preparation for Falcon 0.1.8

Falcon 0.1.8 returns lowercased headers to the client. This *should* be
OK, since well-behaved clients treat headers as case-insensitive. However,
srmock exposes the response headers directly and we do an assert using
them without taking into account case of the header name.

This patch modifies that particular assert to use srmock.header_dict
instead, since in 0.1.8 that is implemented using a case-insensitive
dict.

commit_message:
Ceilometer endpoint doesn't need last slash

The last slash is unnecessary, it only causes redundant slash when
generate api uri, which already treated as a bug in Ceilometer.

Change-Id: I758d76e8edab6e818989bac8e05eb17c6e373546
Closes-Bug: #1269496
backport: havana
ref: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/63279/

commit_message:
Policy management for Climate

Implements policies in Climate with unittests based on Oslo.
Tight integration with Context as it will populate to Context
if user is admin or not based on policy.json

In order to make that work, please add policy.json to /etc/climate

Decorator @policy.authorize allows enforcing policy checks on
controllers.

Implements bp:climate-policy

Change-Id: I94e8fa142e5c5d830b0bea9278e5a47f9904db4c

commit_message:
renamed OS-IDP spec file to OS-FEDERATION

This could have been done as part of a previous change [1] which
expanded the scope of the extension, but it made the diff in gerrit very
difficult to see additional changes. This is ONLY the file rename.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59848/

Change-Id: Ibce5940b61926028774f9c02e533d67ca958662f

commit_message:
Allow different login methods to be used with kombu connections.

Currently it is not possible to modify the login method used with
kombu connections via configuration files, and requires modifying
the source code to actually add a login method in the first place.
This adds a configuration option (and default) which are passed to
the underlying kombu connection.

Unit tests have also been corrected to the best of my knowledge.

Closes-Bug: #1269867
Change-Id: I6ff421a65b0e6f93db76d91e9362cd63d9170299

commit_message:
Add pywbem to global-requirements.txt

The EMC volume driver in Cinder requires the pywbem package to
be available.  This is the first part of the changes required to
enable the package being automatically included by Cinder.

Change-Id: I7fa402f64e7170bb9ebd85bd67efe67e0d1d1736
Partial-Bug: 1204229

commit_message:
Add shard support to the client

The patch adds Shard support of the client. This will allow users to
create and delete shards from Marconi. The API requires the Marconi
instance to be and admin instance. However, there are no checks,
restrictions, yet.

This patch doesn't implement Shards listing. As soon as the
MessageIterator lands, it'll be possible to reuse that code for the
ShardsIterator.

Partially-Implements blueprint: shard-management
Partially-Implements blueprint: python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: I932c98d68a4a81b710dbea75a6bac123b7afaa08

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: test out eatmydata

LD_PRELOAD library that disables all forms of writing data safely to
disk. fsync() becomes a NO-OP, O_SYNC is removed etc.

The idea is to use in testing to get faster test runs where real
durability is not required.

https://launchpad.net/libeatmydata

Change-Id: I97b425dc8ea97007a3ae1865e4d831ed10a47b57

commit_message:
Use the test env JSON to detect remote VM hosts.

This permits devtest_seed to automatically do the right thing in a
TripleO-CI environment. Well, nearly - we still need to fixup some of
the post boot steps, but we should at least have a seed booting from
this.

Change-Id: I1fedc9e41ba2eec96bd21ec618ff48a678a383ce

commit_message:
Use the JSON description to probe the seed VM.

This adds a dependency on jq to let us cleanly write autodetected seed
VM IP addresses into the test file, which will simplify things later
on in our workflow. Using the datafile is preferrable to complex
checks in devtest which is afterall meant to be as much manual as
script.

Change-Id: I81e49d16077c564dd1e5d3e6f6e7a26e7c56ef5c

[{'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:48:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Turns out there isn't any consensus within openstack projects about using hacking, nor is there much of a process to add or remove things from hacking. This results in no set list (across projects) for what's ignored or observed.

This change is a proposal to revert back to where we started: gate on pep8, don't care about hacking stuff.

We should let it get plenty of reviews rather than merging it quickly, and I'm ok with abandoning the patch if we decide to stick with using hacking."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:53:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-10 16:08:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- check-grenade-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/73/65973/1/check/check-grenade-dsvm/56fdf08 : SUCCESS in 30m 25s
"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-01-10 19:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So it's sort of hard to see what all the different things are, but if you look at https://github.com/openstack-dev/hacking/blob/master/hacking/core.py and search for "@flake8ext", you can see what the checks are in there.

Is there a way to opt-in to only particular checks? Like, exclude=H*, include-anyway=H102,H103?

I looked through the list of these things, and I like H102 and H103; the two combined make sure the right license stuff is present in all source files, and I've certainly forgotten that before.

I sort of like H201; that's the no-bare-excepts one. We really only want bare excepts in a very few cases, and for the rest I think it's good to have a linter complain about it.

Other than those three, there's not much that I like, and it does get annoying to have to opt out of the checks whenever a new version comes in, so getting rid of hacking wouldn't make me too sad.

tl;dr: if we can opt in instead of opting out, then keep it, else ditching is okay'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-01-10 20:07:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So, it looks like something like this would work: http://paste.openstack.org/show/WKhDGQbzL4ADoxIRDxvi/

However, if folks just don't want it anymore, that's fine by me too."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2014-01-10 20:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

@Sam, I could get behind using select='}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2014-01-10 23:20:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

soft -1; prefer the opt-in approach

If hacking adds something awesome it'd be nice to have a clear path to stealing.

I'm also fine with leaving it the way it is - but I guess I haven't had to deal with the fallout from upgrades to hacking breaking our builds?"}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-01-11 04:51:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I like the "ignore everything, select a few things" pattern too.

So the next step is to figure out what those are. I'll come up with a short list and propose it over this patch.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-01-11 06:02:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2014-01-11 06:28:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

is everything in the hacking module, bad?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-11 07:44:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Chmouel, no everything in the hacking module is not bad. I simply selected these as a pretty non-controversial subset. I know I started this particular discussion, but I don't think we should spend too much time on it--other things are way more important.

commit_message:
Update RPC code from oslo

The common RPC code has been updated to include the following:
    8575d87af49ea276341908f83c8c51db13afca44
    8b2b0b743e84ceed7841cf470afed6a5da8e1d07
    23f602940c64ba408d77ceb8f5ba0f67ee4a18ef
    6d0a6c3083218cdac52758a8b6aac6b03402c658
    7cac1ac1bd9df36d4e5183afac3b643df10b1d4d
    8159efddabb09dd9b7c99963ff7c9de0a6c62b62

Updated to include the following in modules in openstack-common.conf:
py3kcompat, sslutils, and versionutils.

The update also includes imports from the RPC code

Change-Id: I84c5b8e2b17da0018dd69ecb354d123a609afe98

commit_message:
Make download an action rather than a column

Removed download column.
Created download action that uses containers object_download url.
Fixed spelling of datum in existing action.

Closes-Bug: #1250584
Closes-Bug: #1250599

Change-Id: Ia75080553f97f4eb2b5f4f4c3fc3e550fd318655

commit_message:
Do not filter image list from glance api

Horizon filter glance image list because 'aki', 'ari' type of images
can not be launchable.

However, it is better to provide full capacity with glance in
Horizon.

Reasons:
1. Horizon allow upload those images. It brings confusion if not
show them
2. The filtering strange behavior when pagination is enabled

Changed to show all images in Horizon, but 'aki', 'ari' type of
images are not allowed to launch or create volume.

Change-Id: Ic92fc97d7327bb2525c0155646487dd685e99c79
Closes-Bug: #1257180

commit_message:
Fix updating device names when defaulting

If the virt driver does not support defaulting device names, the default
behaviour of defaulting them in the manager was calling the conductor
block_device_mapping_update method with the wrong arguments, which
caused a TypeError and ultimately a failure to boot the instance.

This patch fixed the signature and adds a test that exercises it so
that it does not regress.

Closes-bug: #1260806
Change-Id: I6116540c9aca4847afacf80b3d1e0c027c364159

[{'created': '2014-01-08 14:20:13.000000000', 'message': "tests: pass /dev/null as config for mongod

On certain system, such as Darwin, the default mongod binary is a
wrapper adding a default configuration file. Let's specify that there's
no configuration file to read, otherwise a log file is used instead of
stdout.

Change-Id: I56c72cd61399405fd57d6e3f2b1f53ca6a395835
"}]
commit_message:
tests: pass /dev/null as config for mongod

On certain system, such as Darwin, the default mongod binary is a
wrapper adding a default configuration file. Let's specify that there's
no configuration file to read, otherwise a log file is used instead of
stdout.

Change-Id: I56c72cd61399405fd57d6e3f2b1f53ca6a395835

commit_message:
Add a swift-enabled version of WordCount to edp-examples

The edp-wordcount example includes source code and instructions on
how to build the jar and run it from the Oozie command line or the
Savanna UI. WordCount will work with hdfs paths, or with swift paths
as long as the proper configs are set.

Change-Id: I9ac728de505d874fd50a6baf75b062d5b622f3d0

commit_message:
Set default bus to SCSI for Power KVM

KVM default bus for x86 are set to ide and virtio for cdrom and
disk, respectively. Adding Power support with bus type SCSI.

Change-Id: I7da4262553f54b48722075534afc888ce87dd03b

commit_message:
Fix use the fact that empty sequences are false

For sequences(strings, lists, tuples), in order to consistent with
pep8 recommendations, 'if len(seq)' should be replaced with 'if seq',
and 'if not len(seq)' should be replaced with 'if not seq'.

Change-Id: Ie7b6afbde07bb57a05b36d92a079c5355945b262
Closes-Bug: #1265688

commit_message:
Remove heat-cli-guide

The heat command line clients are documented now better in the
OpenStack End User Guide:

http://docs.openstack.org/user-guide/content/heat-stack-create.html
http://docs.openstack.org/user-guide/content/heat_client_commands.html

The content here is thus not needed anymore, as the README.rst says:
"This documentation should eventually end up in the OpenStack
documentation repositories `api-site` and `openstack-manuals`."

Change-Id: I297252d7f8eee383ce6252a5db44111630fbe29b

commit_message:
Remove unused common.base module

Base module is already replaced with a module from oslo common code,
but was not removed. This patch must fix this.

Change-Id: I8f5c4da8884db4024d47ca8d1a80dbb648922a31

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-14 15:16:00.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: driver - assert open session before operations

There will be multiple points in the driver where the code
has been state-ful presuming preserved "open session state"
this assumption will have to be baked out of the code a
line at a time.

In this example I'm leaning on the ability to create/join
an open session.

The use of self._session should be treated as "code smell" an
indication that something may be wrong (but not necessarily so).

Change-Id: I48da8faaeba83af3052ae6a35f8fca63dd580fd5
'}]
commit_message:
VMware: driver - assert open session before operations

There will be multiple points in the driver where the code
has been state-ful presuming preserved "open session state"
this assumption will have to be baked out of the code a
line at a time.

In this example I'm leaning on the ability to create/join
an open session.

The use of self._session should be treated as "code smell" an
indication that something may be wrong (but not necessarily so).

Change-Id: I48da8faaeba83af3052ae6a35f8fca63dd580fd5

commit_message:
add a sar filter that makes it report on one line

reading sar input with multiple flags is somewhat problematic,
because it's tons of interspersed headers. So build something with
does a pivot filter to make it possible to get this all on one
line.

Change-Id: I24faf03e0324a4b28d3eb9f7e891f4d99376d7b1

commit_message:
Configure plugins by name

To configure core plugin or service plugins, instead of using class names,
simpler names can also be used, ex:

service_plugins = router, firewall, lbaas

For compatibility with previous versions, the class name of a plugin can be
specified instead of its entrypoint name, ex:

service_plugins = router, neutron.services.firewall.fwaas_plugin.FirewallPlugin, lbaas

DocImpact

Implements: blueprint config-plugin-by-name
Change-Id: Ia4aaa1d305b160a4d6dab9e227c744727a4c78c2

[{'created': '2014-01-14 22:38:19.000000000', 'message': "Symlink correct element install type

The source-repositories element will now create a symlink under the
install.d hook directory pointing to the directory (or file) that
contains the implementation for the chosen install type.

For example, the nova element would provide:

nova/install.d/74-nova
nova/install.d/nova-package-install/74-nova
nova/install.d/nova-source-install/74-nova

source-repositories will create the following symlink for the package
install type:

$TMP_HOOKS_PATH/install.d/nova-install -> nova-package-install

Or, for the source install type:

$TMP_HOOKS_PATH/install.d/nova-install -> nova-source-install

nova/install.d/74-nova then executes dib-run-parts against nova-install,
and the correct install type is executed. Note that the implementation
in install.d/74-nova is element specific. It's likely most elements will
just call dib-run-parts <element-name>-install, however they could just
as easily execute other scripts, run common install code before or after
dib-run-parts, etc.

Change-Id: I1bfaf39e5a98b2af904fbc6d674dbada30b27ed9
"}, {'created': '2014-01-15 19:26:51.000000000', 'message': "Symlink correct element install type

directory.

directories.

For example, the nova element would provide:

source-repositories will create the following symlink for the package

Or, for the source install type:

This requires a minor change in dib-run-parts to dereference symlinks when

commit_message:
Symlink correct element install type

The source-repositories element will now symlink the install scripts
corresponding to the set install type for an element into the install.d
directory.

Different install types are implemented by elements by writing scripts to do
the install type under install.d/<element-name>-<install-type>-install
directories.

For example, the nova element would provide:

nova/install.d/nova-package-install/74-nova
nova/install.d/nova-source-install/74-nova

source-repositories will create the following symlink for the package
install type:

$TMP_HOOKS_PATH/install.d/74-nova -> nova-package-install/74-nova

Or, for the source install type:

$TMP_HOOKS_PATH/install.d/74-nova -> nova-source-install/74-nova

Change-Id: I1bfaf39e5a98b2af904fbc6d674dbada30b27ed9

commit_message:
dib-run-parts should dereference symlinks

dib-run-parts should dereference symlinks, and if they point to an
executable file, execute that file as a script. This can be accomplished
by using the xtype predicate in the find command instead of the type
predicate.

This change is needed so that we can dynamically symlink hook scripts
into hook directories such as install.d at runtime to support different
install types.

Change-Id: I933e7f4b4dcf16956841d8c14aa63b0f9a18fc5d

commit_message:
Adds user_data extension to nova.api.v3.extensions

Although the user_data extension does not create a resource
or controller extension and only implements server.create and
server.create.deserialize entry points it does need to be listed as
a nova.api.v3.extension entry point as the whitelist check
operates on that entry point.

This does not add any runtime overhead and allows user_data to be
specified in the whitelist.

Also adds missing discoverable policy for the user data extension

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Ia8ac2fa150ab2fe9c1848c5a7ddc416952adf0e4

Fixes: bug #1269475

If using the default lvmiscsi driver for cinder, rhel and ubuntu look in
different places for their include files. At the moment, the following line
gets added to /etc/tgt/targets.conf on rhel systems:

include /var/lib/cinder/volumes/*

This patch changes it to the correct line:

include /etc/cinder/volumes/*

commit_message:
set correct include line for rhel/centos in /etc/tgt/targets.conf

Fixes: bug #1269475

If using the default lvmiscsi driver for cinder, rhel and ubuntu look in
different places for their include files. At the moment, the following line
gets added to /etc/tgt/targets.conf on rhel systems:

include /var/lib/cinder/volumes/*

This patch changes it to the correct line:

include /etc/cinder/volumes/*

Change-Id: I43b5a58b3cd77a2218cdaec3c67f3289a4e10d50

commit_message:
Fix bug in the api 'os-migrations'

The return is not what we are expecting:
  migration-list: 'unicode' object has no attribute 'iteritems'

The conversion of the object nova.objects.Migration into a list
is not applied automatically.

Change-Id: I3f2bf1a4c53e22c66954e1069a1bcd618a1fd52b

commit_message:
Add _() to rackspace resource strings

As part of fix to bug #1249217, all the translation strings were
included in _(), but rackspace resources were ignored.
This change is to fix translation strings in rackspace resources.

Change-Id: I2a422746693136636cc137e2e9cc1bd3a7e6bb01
Closes-Bug: #1261545

@Jason, yes, and they're currently in our .gitignore as well. I forced them to be included in this patch since testr needs you to run

  testr init

before the first test run to initialize the test repository. Without these files in the initial commit, the gate tests wouldn't run because there was no initial repository. Forcing the repo files in the initial commit was basically a hack to make that work, but if there's a better way, I'm certainly willing to remove them."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-12-13 15:55:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

  runtests: commands[1] | python contrib/bin/run_tests.py

I see. Is it possible to write a test_results_contrib.html then.'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-01-13 22:56:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

@stevebaker, I haven't looked into it, but afaik, that's part of the configuration of the gating jobs. The test running code in the contrib tests was cribbed heavily from the testr plugin from distutils, so it does the same thing that the existing test runs do. The goal is to prevent continuous regressions from popping up in the contrib tree since people consistently make changes to contrib resources but don't run the contrib tests. If its a hard requirement, I'd prefer this patch is accepted as-is and a bug filed for the results stuff so I have some time to look  into it. In the meantime, we can put the kibosh on contrib regressions."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-01-14 21:18:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Remove Create Backup Action For Non-Active

the "create backup" action is incorrectly shown for a non-active
database instance in the database instances table. now, only if the
instance is active, will the action/button appear.

in addition, non-active instances are now excluded from the dropdown
in the create-backup workflow.

Change-Id: Id9fdeab84ad91b96ba1a9f07ee6d1af87b6320f7
Closes-Bug: #1268260

commit_message:
New message added informing how to exit fullscreen mode.

Fixing this bug in the full screen mode involves patching it
on noVNC codebase.
This patch adds a comment for how to exit the full screen
mode using the browser's back button.

Change-Id: Ibcf510efadd6a1f29e0b2693ce9e332d54652d62
Closes-Bug:1251196

commit_message:
Using staticmethod to mock LibvirtDriver._supports_direct_io

The actual test is wrong, but does not failed because the signature
of the fake method "connection_supports_direct_io_stub" accepts an
ulimited number of args.

commit_message:
O'Reilly Edit: Clarification of the Scheduler

This modification removes the discussion of flavor and flavor sizing
from the Scheduler section. While flavors sizing could be appropriate
for this section, it requires defining flavors, which might cause the
discussion to tangent.

Change-Id: I3fb63ec4f079ffa590498c22697c3f3b116c8412

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netifaces  package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: Ia8d5ce8152237a67da4828f3c70cf9f367d44d41
Partial-Bug: #1266513
"}]
commit_message:
Whitelist external netifaces requirement

* tox.ini(testenv.install_command): Use the --allow-external and
--allow-insecure options so that pip 1.5 and later will assent to
retrieve the netifaces  package even though it's not hosted on PyPI.
The --allow-insecure option is aliased to a clearer
--allow-unverified wording in 1.5, but the old form is being used to
avoid breaking users of 1.4.x and will be valid at least through
1.6.x according to comments in the pip source.

Change-Id: Ia8d5ce8152237a67da4828f3c70cf9f367d44d41
Partial-Bug: #1266513

Remove unused arg `instances`

In function VolumeTableMixIn._set_id_if_nameless(), we
define arg `instances`, but we never use it.

Closes-Bug: #1269200

[{'created': '2014-01-15 23:14:18.000000000', 'message': 'ERRORs in ceilometer-acentral log after succesful tempest run

swift pollster tries to run against all projects (even those not
associated with the project-scoped token). this causes issues when
keystoneauth middleware in swift tries to validate token with
project.

change logic to only work against the project the token is related
to.

Change-Id: I26db9ffad5e787cb064b14c912fc76e63b66ffb7
Closes-Bug: #1268730
'}]
commit_message:
ERRORs in ceilometer-acentral log after succesful tempest run

swift pollster tries to run against all projects (even those not
associated with the project-scoped token). this causes issues when
keystoneauth middleware in swift tries to validate token with
project.

change logic to only work against the project the token is related
to.

Change-Id: I26db9ffad5e787cb064b14c912fc76e63b66ffb7
Closes-Bug: #1268730

commit_message:
Alter is_locked() helper comment

The is_locked() helper method comment
was created when we used threading2 but
since we don't use it anymore we need to
adjust that comment to reflect the current
usage.

Change-Id: I06051fb2d65b8c871e916d7e64e6056ecff3afda

after checking the git commit history, what I get is that

commit_message:
Change instances config_drive column from string to Boolean

config drive feature was added early in commit d963e25906b75a48c75b6e589deb2a53f75d6ee3,
config_drive column is varchar type but only store Boolean value, so when using
nova boot --config-drive true to build instances, a string 'True' is stored in DB,
The function still works because a string is regard as True in statement, this patch
changes column type from varchar to Boolean, and changes the string 'True' to a Boolean
type.

Closes-Bug: 1193438

Change-Id: I6c2951a890dc213a053e0ccbc0685ecf0afbdf1a

commit_message:
Fix exception catch when CPU Host features cannot be parsed

libvirt.VIR_ERR_NO_SUPPORT is of type integer, so it will
never be thrown by libvirt. Change it to libvirt.libvirtError
which will be thrown by the current implementation of libvirt.
Add testcase.

Related-Bug: #1262723

Change-Id: I98b95e48ac647784a751b6eb405c861004dd136b

commit_message:
Adds support of custom project domains

Add the ability to pass project_domain_id / project_domain_name to keystone
via CLI params or environment variables such as OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_ID or
OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_NAME.

Change-Id: I785c0a21a1542dff479b1e939f33c85d06bbdb09
Closes-Bug: 1198171
Signed-off-by: Bo Tang <btang@cs.utsa.edu>

Could you include some information on how this works? I sourced glance.bash_completion and it seemed to work. 

Also, novaclient has had this functionality for a few years and it has evolved a bit. There may be things in there we want to adopt.

Please let me know your thoughts :)"}, {'account_id': 9552, 'date': '2013-12-06 10:22:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

When you source glance.bash_completion it registers the _glance function to complete arguments of the glance command. Usually this script is put into the directory /etc/bash_completion.d/ so that you don't have to source it manually.

Each time the tab key is pressed after the glance command, _glance is called, which gets the available options by running 'glance bash_completion' and chooses the appropriate completion using compgen.

I have checked novaclient, it has 3 extra functions:
- cache output of "nova bash-complete" to run faster
- distinguish between flags and commands (based on already typed text)
- use cached info from ~/.novaclient to complete ids, etc.

I think the first two could be added to glance.bash_completion, the third not really since I couldn't find any cache for glanceclient.'}, {'account_id': 9552, 'date': '2013-12-09 14:27:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-09 15:02:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Support bash completion

Added support for bash completion, the implementation
is based on python-cinderclient and python-novaclient.

The completer function caches output of "glance bash-completion"
to run faster, and distinguishes between flags and commands
(based on already typed text).

Change-Id: I22b9117fa0dd28e351c2d6062237216424fd88cd

commit_message:
Undeprecate run_tests.sh

tox is not completely serving our needs,
it has some startup costs, and the ways
to do many of the standard tasks (run until
first failure, for example) are not documented.

Until we have a full replacement for
run_tests.sh, keep it for documentation and
ensuring the unit tests are fast and easy to run.

This change also modifies the flag for running to first failure.

Change-Id: I879db5bd94bfdb323f85356ace67042ff262cf18

[{'created': '2013-10-14 22:38:33.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Fix spurious backing file existence check.

Bug 1195877

The problem lies with the truncation of backing file names at the
first underscore character. On a reboot, nova-compute checks the
backing images exist. Typically, they will do; however, instead
of looking for an "ephemeral_XXX" file, it hunts for "ephemeral".
This won't exist, triggering code that attempts to pull the whole
image again from glance(!)

Lacking credentials, the attempt to fetch the image will fail,
ultimately resulting in the instance going to an ERROR state.

Change-Id: Iabcc7a1ffd248c22a747a1ddc7863d2b386d409a
(cherry picked from commit 65386c91910ee03d947c2b8bcc226a53c30e060a)
'}]
commit_message:
libvirt: Fix spurious backing file existence check.

Bug 1195877

The problem lies with the truncation of backing file names at the
first underscore character. On a reboot, nova-compute checks the
backing images exist. Typically, they will do; however, instead
of looking for an "ephemeral_XXX" file, it hunts for "ephemeral".
This won't exist, triggering code that attempts to pull the whole
image again from glance(!)

Lacking credentials, the attempt to fetch the image will fail,
ultimately resulting in the instance going to an ERROR state.

Change-Id: Iabcc7a1ffd248c22a747a1ddc7863d2b386d409a
(cherry picked from commit 65386c91910ee03d947c2b8bcc226a53c30e060a)

commit_message:
VMware: Take the volume size from the user input

When we create a volume from an image or a snapshot, we need to
take the size of the volume from the user input and validate whether
the size is appropriate instead of taking the image size as the
volume size directly.

Change-Id: I7e3f40559b3055f08a7f6dcf041458165ff8032b

commit_message:
VMware: Take the volume size from the user input

When we create a volume from an image or a snapshot, we need to
take the size of the volume from the user input and validate whether
the size is appropriate instead of taking the image size as the
volume size directly.

Change-Id: I3ea6dee0a1688e5038a05337b295c699f81267d1
Closes-Bug: #1237557

commit_message:
Fix negative unit test for sec group rules

Ensure the test fails because the security group
rule could not be created, and not because the security
group was deleted before creating the rule.

Closes-Bug: #1268561

Change-Id: Ib2ea8c4507862d7bb343ce5181cf018b3cdf4b73

Adds test_list_XX_fields cases to list some fields

This change adds test_list_XX_fields cases to test
if listing some fields works well. A related url
example is 'v2.0/networks.json?fields=id'.

Change-Id: Ic41d83ec394b6bd7767d0523a8b21614468e0f6a

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-10 11:40:29.000000000', 'message': "Move driver initizialization check into the method

Volumes and backups managers' methods are decorated with
`require_initialized_driver` which checks whether the driver has been
initialized or not. The decorator fails with a `DriverNotInitialized`
exception if the driver hasn't been initialized.

This early failure leaves volumes and backups in a wrong status which is
not just confusing for the user but it also makes it difficult to do
anything with the resources after they've been left in a 'bogus' status.

For example, when a volume creation is requested, the volume is first
created in the database and its status is set to 'creating'. Then the
scheduler will pick an available volume node and send the task to it. If
the driver has not been initialized, the volume status will be left as
'creating' instead of 'error'.

This patch fixes that issue by moving the driver initialization check
into the various manager's methods. In some cases this check is done at
the very beginning of the method, in some others - either to avoid code
duplication or because the lines above the check made sense to be
executed first - this check is done later in the method.

Change-Id: I2610be6ba1aa7df417f1a1f7bb27af30273e4814
Closes-bug: #1242942

commit_message:
Move driver initialization check into the method

Volumes and backups managers' methods are decorated with
`require_initialized_driver` which checks whether the driver has been
initialized or not. The decorator fails with a `DriverNotInitialized`
exception if the driver hasn't been initialized.

This early failure leaves volumes and backups in a wrong status which is
not just confusing for the user but it also makes it difficult to do
anything with the resources after they've been left in a 'bogus' status.

For example, when a volume creation is requested, the volume is first
created in the database and its status is set to 'creating'. Then the
scheduler will pick an available volume node and send the task to it. If
the driver has not been initialized, the volume status will be left as
'creating' instead of 'error'.

This patch fixes that issue by moving the driver initialization check
into the various manager's methods. In some cases this check is done at
the very beginning of the method, in some others - either to avoid code
duplication or because the lines above the check made sense to be
executed first - this check is done later in the method.

Change-Id: I2610be6ba1aa7df417f1a1f7bb27af30273e4814
Closes-bug: #1242942

commit_message:
Improve node-validate command output

The Ironic API improved the validation output to return the reason why an
interface failed to validate[1], this patch makes the necessary changes
to the client to reflect that change.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/63477/

Change-Id: I6e5cca0965febcbec9895d236ca7aee18fbca7db

commit_message:
reduce default token duration to one hour

- reduces number of active tokens that have to be persisted, especially
  where clients are needlessly regenerating tokens
- reduces the window of publishing token revocation events (you only
  have to publish events from the last hour)
- reduces the window of the token revocation list (similar to the above)

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact

Implements: bp reduce-default-token-duration
Change-Id: Ia548f7e981690edab56c51fdcab9102245aced3e

I found this issue by accident. I was running RedStack with a user that had a colorized Bash prompt. Some non-printable characters were making their way into my SSH files during staging.

Below is code that demonstrates the general problem on Ubuntu 12.04.2.

---
$ sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash test
$ sudo su test -
$ echo "echo hello" > ~/.bashrc
$ exit
$ sudo -Hiu test cat /dev/null > ~/test
$ cat ~/test
hello
---

Questions/Comments for reviewers:
* With this patch, file is written as $HOST_USERNAME instead of `whoami`. But as far as I can tell, these are always the same.
* With this patch, ownership is updated. Again, I don't know under what conditions $HOST_USERNAME and `whoami` will differ.
* With this patch, timestamp is updated. But that is the case with cat too.
* With this patch, permissions are changed. But that is the case with cat too (umask).'}, {'account_id': 9683, 'date': '2014-01-03 05:04:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Fix incorrect redirection when staging SSH files.

Existing code uses sudo and cat with redirection to stage SSH files
(e.g. id_rsa). But the redirection redirects the output of the sudo
command as well as the cat command. Thus, any stdout from the
interactive shell (e.g. .bashrc) can end up in the staged files.
Remove the redirection and use dd instead (as is used to copy
staged files to their final destination).

Closes-Bug: #1266557
Change-Id: Ia976bc309a282e4917e89afca52b6986bab26f07

commit_message:
add log for _get_images method

The _get_images method in glance/registry/api/v1/images.py doesn't
give logs when catch exceptions. Two logs for two different
exceptions will be very useful for debug.

Change-Id: I5725da0dafdb9909de1c31734b3c1c225483ca66
Closes-Bug:#1263871

commit_message:
Fix incorrect assertTrue usage

Several self.assertTrue(len(returned_list)) statements exist,
which don't make any sense as we're testing an integer length
as a boolean.  Instead test the returned list length matches
the list passed in to stub the request.

Change-Id: I713c3a6afcc93ebb2a8f7ffde45aade2154ebf2c

Bump hacking to 0.8 and get python 3.x compatibility

Bump hacking dependency to 0.8 to get python 3.x compatibility
Fixes done in order to avoid errors after enabling hacking 0.8

Change-Id: Ic878fe2e1bd3f65f7f95a9b5c7a192dac81b749d
Closes-Bug: #1257282

commit_message:
baremetal: stop deployment if block devices are not available

In this case deploy-helper should abort immediately and make sure
that the instance's status set to ERROR.

Closes-Bug: 1251525
Change-Id: Ic09f171edb0fe3a449c7adfe622ab48709c73252

[{'created': '2014-01-10 21:09:32.000000000', 'message': "Update `openstack/common/context.py' from Oslo

The current version of context.py imports uuidutils.
The module uuidutils has been removed from openstack-common.conf.
Consequently, context.py needs to use uuid instead.

Change-Id: I657e20ac39fbace60f230652912a4bf792836206
Closes-Bug: #1253497
"}, {'created': '2014-01-14 00:38:01.000000000', 'message': "Remove 'openstack/common/context.py'

context.py is not used anywhere in Glance. Consequently, we can get
rid of it.
Also, context.py is the only file left using uuidutils.

Change-Id: I657e20ac39fbace60f230652912a4bf792836206
Closes-Bug: #1253497
"}]
commit_message:
Remove 'openstack/common/context.py'

context.py is not used anywhere in Glance. Consequently, we can get
rid of it.
Also, context.py is the only file left using uuidutils.

Change-Id: I657e20ac39fbace60f230652912a4bf792836206
Closes-Bug: #1253497

[{'created': '2014-01-15 21:54:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fix error installing language pack in Guest Image

    A script in the element for ubuntu-guest does not appear to be
    running the apt-get update command.  02-baseline-tools had a
    package which no longer matches the default name which is part of
    the base image.  I removed the apt-get update which was not working
    and deferred to the call in 03-baseline-tools.  I then moved our
    02-baseline-tools to 04-baseline-tools so that it runs after 03

Change-Id: I1a9ad225f9a2e0fa976be02180dbbe5e24c3bdea
'}]
commit_message:
Fix error installing language pack in Guest Image

    A script in the element for ubuntu-guest does not appear to be
    running the apt-get update command.  02-baseline-tools had a
    package which no longer matches the default name which is part of
    the base image.  I removed the apt-get update which was not working
    and deferred to the call in 03-baseline-tools.  I then moved our
    02-baseline-tools to 04-baseline-tools so that it runs after 03

Change-Id: I1a9ad225f9a2e0fa976be02180dbbe5e24c3bdea

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-14 17:11:32.000000000', 'message': 'Wait for tgtd socket to be available

tgtd returns execution control and backgrounds itself almost immediately
and before it has made it's listening socket available. This can cause a
race condition as the tgtd socket is not available when tgtadm is run,
resulting in an error:

commit_message:
Wait for tgtd socket to be available

tgtd returns execution control and backgrounds itself almost immediately
and before it has made it's listening socket available. This can cause a
race condition as the tgtd socket is not available when tgtadm is run,
resulting in an error:

failed to send request hdr to tgt daemon

Add a function to check if the socket is available before moving on to
calling tgtadm, and a wait_for helper function we can use.  We'll
check for the socket every 0.5 seconds, for up to 5 seconds.

I'm seeing this issue on almost every deploy using a ramdisk built from
Fedora 20. I'm not sure if something has changed in tgtd, but this
behavior is documented since Fedora 18 at least. In the systemd script
for tgtd, there is actually "sleep 5" to work around the problem.

See Also: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=848942

Change-Id: Iffa9fc63393309ca653d592dff17316ecbea3e09

[{'created': '2013-12-18 19:25:28.000000000', 'message': 'Neutron: make router creation for tenant isolation optional

When neutron is enabled, everytime credentials are retrieved a
router is created and connected to the internal and external
networks. Many tests actually do not need this, and by making
router setup optional tests could run faster and the load on
the neutron l3 agent will be reduced.

In order to avoid breakage with potential out-of-tree tests,
this patch still assumes that by default the router is created
unless the caller specifically asks not to.

Change-Id: I89d4aead38a68c9222c5b0cd5dd0386705eb9648
Closes-Bug: 1262334

commit_message:
Create only necessary resources for compute v2 and network tests

This patch leverages the set_network_resources method in order to allow
tempest api tests for compute v2 and network to create only those
network resources which are required by the test

Related-Bug: #1262334

Change-Id: I89d4aead38a68c9222c5b0cd5dd0386705eb9648

commit_message:
Change libvirt log level from debug to info+

Commit eb68676e460834831b0b72348f9e016b3341f3aa changed the log
level for libvirt to debug, but no useful information is given
at debug level.

Devstack makes the system logs unusable for a typical developer
workstation with the current log_level of DEBUG.  Hopefully INFO
is a reasonable middle ground.

commit_message:
Add openstack.common.uuidutils to Solum

uuid will be used widely in Solum. There is a library in
oslo-incubator for working with uuid. This patch adds
uuidutils to openstack.comon forlder in Solum folder.

Change-Id: Ia9f99ff1f9d7a1e7863b3758603cd5860a99164c
Closes-Bug: #1267267

commit_message:
Support inexact filtering on attributes

Being able to specify inexact filters on attributes is an important
part of ensuring the size of collections returned by list API calls
is minimized

DocImpact

Partially implements bp filtering-backend-support

Change-Id: If81f6644217f121afeed00b867f369ec257e63b3

commit_message:
Enable Firewall as a Service plugin

Aims to enable FWaaS plugin when using Neutron in the gate.
It will allow us to run Tempest tests against devstack-gate.

Change-Id: Iaf751730554c226a750d4deea61d7011a180d669
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Test server create with ephemeral disk

This patch creates new flavor, which includes ephemeral disk.
Then ssh into the instance to get partition information. We can't
get partition device name , this depends on image. So we compare
the number of partitions to confirm ephemeral disk is created.

Change-Id: I3183746cf35b2acbf443a0b52b211982758bcf87

commit_message:
Add more functional tests

These test cases are also in solum/tests/api/v1/test_functional.py but they run
against pecan test app. Once we have a gate which runs these new functional
tests cases, then we could remove pecan functional tests.

Change-Id: I969558db142b66d92e0428a07516b944643a984b

commit_message:
Make use of REST client from tempest project

1. run_tests.sh: Add tempest source tree to PYTHONPATH before running tests.

2. Adjust tests to use tempest client.

3. Enable authentication in devstack solum service.

For this to work, tempest must be installed. Patch [1] is submitted for the same.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/64062

Change-Id: Idaaf637c066444e02cd35da1f5dba717f0d61c6b

commit_message:
Omit openstack/common/ in test coverage reports

These methods are tested in oslo-incubator not in rally,
so we should just ignore test covarage of them.

Change-Id: I8fb6a4be1968653ef982f60c896dcc6a2bf65625

commit_message:
Add cookbook support for Openstack Orchestration

This new cookbook supports the installation and configuraiton for heat services.
More pedantic patches will follow to make Rubocop happy.

Implements: blueprint heat-support

Change-Id: I8b734b7124c49190a68acc4d0da28a31da03ac57

commit_message:
Optimize libvirt live migration workflow at source

During live migration, after instance migrated to destination, we
call Hypervisor destroy to clean the instance, this can be omitted
because it doesn't exist in source server already. This patch changes
cleanup to a public method to driver, split instance destroy to two
step:

1. destroy instance in the Hypervisor
2. cleanup instance resources(block device, network)

Change-Id: I65e711c03fee7342b1e2bc4f9459baae7729f911
Closes-bug: 1240820

commit_message:
Implement neutron metering resources

Two new resources were added:
 - MeteringLabel
 - MeteringRule

These resources are realisation in heat neutron's
resources: metering-label and metering-label-rule.

Change-Id: I700dac3fa12d8202b873957542dba6ee1605c3e3
Implements: blueprint neutron-metering-resources

Add stack id and resource id in logs

Where applicable, the stack and resource id's will be added in the logs
that reference those stacks and/or resources.

blueprint log-resource-stack-id

Co-Authored-By: Daniel Givens <daniel.givens@rackspace.com>

Sync strutils from oslo which fix safe_encode under py3, this gets
heat CLI to not output in bytes.

(there is a bit more to be done for complete py3 support)

84d461 Fix a bug in safe_encode where it returns a bytes object in py3

Change-Id: Ic29c0037bfbc612e954045c95edca68f273c4a1a
'}]
commit_message:
Sync strutils from oslo

Sync strutils from oslo which fix safe_encode under py3, this gets
heat CLI to not output in bytes.

(there is a bit more to be done for complete py3 support)

84d461 Fix a bug in safe_encode where it returns a bytes object in py3

Change-Id: Ic29c0037bfbc612e954045c95edca68f273c4a1a

commit_message:
Run neutron-debug with admin tenant in neutron-adv-test

Because neutron-debug create-probe needs admin role only, demo tenants
cannot create ports. neutron-debug is wrapped in order to run it only
with admin tenant.

Change-Id: Ib65e8639858c597345c6a5fdc0192b40f34a0300
Closes-Bug: #1269090

commit_message:
Move to use "get_password" instead of "{user,service,db}_password"

The user_password, service_password and db_password functions are redundant
since they simply call "secret". Creates a get_password function that
will accept a "type" of db, service or user.

All instances of these calls have been changed to call get_password.

Interim commit that keeps the service,db and user functions in order to
merge other changes.

Change-Id: Iba4a611b387d0975e8a23cc758d2ac7dec8210ad
Partial-Bug: #1195915

commit_message:

autobuilding documentation from source code.

Add binding:host_id when creating port for probe

When probe is created it needs to have correct bindings otherwise port
is marked as dead.

commit_message:
Don't install scripts straight to /usr/local/bin

This results in more then just the openstack clients getting installed
to /usr/local/bin. In my case /usr/local/bin/pip was part of the
python-novaclient virtualenv and being used globally. Instead link to
what we want inside the virtualenv.

Change-Id: If44b397cdd80c46bf5a2a86d7369a4d74e09b58c

commit_message:
Changed HDP plugin to use ports from config

To form cluster info URIs for HDP plugin use proper port from
configurations. Covered with unit tests.

Change-Id: I4692b06694295f4103a93dbb0087375e2499c664
Closes-Bug: #1204076

This is great. It's a way to codify what it means to have a cache with different storage backends - pluggable key-value storage.

Some thoughts regarding locking - I think that's necessary primarily for the sake of demonstrating that whatever key-value store is used, we're expecting the implementation to have transactional semantics for reads and writes.

Regarding configuration, I imagine many key-value storage backends will want to expose authentication parameters (host, port, username, password). IMO, supporting richer configuration should become more clear (and easier to explore) in a future patch."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-08-20 11:27:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-20 11:59:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-06-11 09:57:13.000000000', 'message': "Implement cache abstraction layer

This patch implements a cache abstraction library that can be extended
and supports multiple back-ends.

The patch being submitted defines the library's API and implements a
first in-memory back-end, which is the default one and can be used for
development purposes.

Configuration variables
=======================

The library introduces 2 configuration variables:

    * cache_backend: The back-end to use.
    * cache_prefix: A prefix to prepend to every key.

Installing back-ends
====================

Back-ends are loaded using stevedore, which means, they most be
installed as entry_points under the `openstack.common.cache.backends`
namespace. See `setup.cfg`.

Back-ends Configuration
=======================

As for now, every back-end is expected to define the configuration
parameters it needs that will later accessed through the `GroupAttr`
instance passed to it. Before a back-end instance is created, the
`register_opts` classmethod will be called.

Things I'm not sure about
=========================

    * Is there a better way to let back-ends register their configuration
    parameters?

    * Is a separate group really needed? (I personally prefer to keep
    those configs isolated from app's ones)

    * Is the whole locking stuff really needed? What about just using
    .get / .pop and catch errors?

NOTE: Some of the ideas where taken from Django's cache library and others
from Oslo's memcached module.

Implements blueprint cache-backend-abstraction

Change-Id: Ic2a84ecef949fb28a7d05fe1b2c54ca91da3983c

Configuration variables

The library introduces 2 configuration variables:

Installing back-ends
====================

Back-ends are loaded using stevedore, which means, they most be
installed as entry_points under the `openstack.common.cache.backends`
namespace. See `setup.cfg`.

Back-ends Configuration
=======================

As for now, every back-end is expected to register the configuration
parameters it needs. The conf instance and cache group will be passed
to each backend in order to allow this.

Things I'm not sure about
=========================

    * Is there a better way to let back-ends register their configuration
    parameters?

    * Is a separate group really needed? (I personally prefer to keep
    those configs isolated from app's ones)

    * Is the whole locking stuff really needed? What about just using
    .get / .pop and catch errors?

NOTE: Some of the ideas where taken from Django's cache library and others
from Oslo's memcached module.

Implements blueprint cache-backend-abstraction

commit_message:
Implement cache abstraction layer

This patch implements a cache abstraction library that can be extended
and supports multiple back-ends.

The patch being submitted defines the library's API and implements a
first in-memory back-end, which is the default one and can be used for
development purposes.

Configuration variables
=======================

The library introduces 1 optional configuration variable:

    * cache_url: The cache url. For example:
        memory://?default_ttl=2

`cache.register_oslo_config` needs to be called explicitly with a
ConfigOpts instance in order to register this parameter. The library can
be used without oslo.config.

Installing back-ends
====================

Back-ends are loaded using stevedore, which means, they most be
installed as entry_points under the `openstack.common.cache.backends`
namespace. See `setup.cfg`.

NOTE: Some of the ideas where taken from Django's cache library and others
from Oslo's memcached module.

Implements blueprint cache-backend-abstraction

Change-Id: Ic2a84ecef949fb28a7d05fe1b2c54ca91da3983c

commit_message:
Fix keystone get_service_url filtering

We are retrieving the services from keystone, so there
is no need to do filtering of the catalog, since we are
directly dealing with services endpoints.

Change-Id: I9a40207e2dee2e5bc268b9516daa74a3c6cf2352

subject: Changed Vanilla plugin to use ports from config

2014-01-09 10:27:08.086 17482 TRACE savanna.context 

The problem is that with this patch EDP job manager tries to connect Oozie service by port 8080, this is default port set in config 'oozie.base.url' in oozie-default.xml. 
 
But as you may know Oozie included into savanna vanilla image starts on port 11000 by default. It's because actual config which sets oozie's http port is  OOZIE_HTTP_PORT in /opt/oozie/bin/oozie-sys.sh.

Right now I can't say how to tell oozie apply port from 'oozie.base.url' in oozie-site.xml. We need investigate this, but current implemetation will not work.'}, {'account_id': 7125, 'date': '2014-01-09 11:58:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

In addition I agree to land this patch with hardcoded Oozie port 11000 but need to file a bug about this and leave TODO mark.'}, {'account_id': 9718, 'date': '2014-01-09 14:35:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Why 'oozie.base.url' in oozie-default.xml uses 8080 port but not 11000 which is default for oozie? Maybe we could change value in config? It will not resolve the problem that oozie doesn't use config to start but will make code more consistent."}, {'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2014-01-09 16:03:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

-1 due to the issue from Alex."}, {'account_id': 7125, 'date': '2014-01-09 16:51:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Yevgen, It seems 'oozie.base.url' is some legacy config in Oozie which is never read during oozie starting up.
I'd prefer to don't change this default in oozie-defaults.xml because it mislead users that changing port will change oozie behaviour during startup."}, {'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2014-01-09 18:49:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-09 20:15:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

[{'created': '2013-12-27 10:50:01.000000000', 'message': 'Changed Vanilla plugin to use ports from config

To form cluster info URIs for Vanilla plugin use proper port from

commit_message:
WIP: Integrate Solum CLI into python-openstackclient

This integrates Devdatta's assembly show command into the OSC.

Since Solum is not an official OpenStack project, we may not integrate the
Solum features needed into the OpenStack Client (OSC) itself.  Thus, we must
indicate that the OSC is a requirement and make a Solum plugin.

Implements: blueprint solum-minimal-cli
Change-Id: I4b31d088dfca9436698c64127d2ce006cab9e367

commit_message:
explicitly set rpc_backend in cinder.conf

Implements: blueprint centos-rhel-for-block
Fixes: bug #1269432

The following is a default value in cinder:

rpc_backend=cinder.openstack.common.rpc.impl_kombu

Using RDO (rhel/centos) packages, this gets overridden in
/usr/share/nova/cinder-dist.conf to 'impl_qpid'.

In order to cleanly set this back to the default value (which is what we
want as a default in the cookbooks), we need to explicitly set this in
cinder.conf

Change-Id: I5bd0c6ed95a6d02202b19708f15a58ec43a2fe6c

commit_message:
Close SSH connections in Cloud Servers resource

Previously, it was possible that a failed stack or hung script could
cause an SSH connection to remain open.  This ensures that the SSH
connections are always closed.

Closes-Bug: #1267173
Change-Id: Ie31ddb8370349ad67c7f63916e6b3b202904da23

commit_message:
Fix heat-keystone-setup error when try to create heat user

Unset OS_SERVICE_TOKEN and OS_SERVICE_ENDPOINT temporarily to make
sure this command can run even if the OS_SERVICE_TOKEN and
OS_SERVICE_ENDPOIN exist in shell environment.
Remove die_if_not_set in get_data function, because there maybe no
data in get_data function, for example, if the heat user does not
exist, the die_if_not_set will be in error.
Remove die_if_not_set after keystone user-list for the same reason.

Change-Id: I132f975ac2da21e6ad7431ae326ad9bd538e4696
Closes-Bug: #1266670

Make nova-network use Instance objects

This converts existing direct-to-database instance queries
use objects.

Related to blueprint nova-network-objects

commit_message:
Make nova-network use Service object

There is a very small usage of service data in nova-network, which
can be converted to use the object method. Since it results in
the same database call as before, the tests need no change.

Related to blueprint nova-network-objects

Change-Id: Ie6ef37a3508c0ef3481d0217d3d085b855cfdc70

commit_message:
Skip Nova exercises if Nova is not enabled

This allows for ./exercises.sh to complete sucessfully when nova is not
enabled / installed.

Change-Id: If969e14f5106c15007146e8fad1da27d131828c8

commit_message:
Saner debug log message generation

For some reason building the debug log would include spaces in the
message elements and join on the empty string. It makes much more sense
to just build the list and join on the space.

Change-Id: Idd82787b87518c56122d0b13551f84529306337c

commit_message:
Makes 'expires_at' not appear if not set on task

Fixes bug: 1267148

'expires_at' on a task must be set only after the executor succeeds or
fails on a task. Before the task has finished, there shouldn't be any
'expires_at' set on the task. This change fixes the ResponseSerializer
to not show 'expires_at' if it is not set.

Change-Id: I9880cc03b9d6f0dd98388fcf0d1bdc9c34dd6c0e

commit_message:
Add binding:host_id when creating port for probe

When probe is created it needs to have correct bindings otherwise port
is marked as dead.

Change-Id: I64441fbe802aab068c129c9647c7144fcd4c50a1
Partial-Bug: #1262785

Honestly there seems like a painful amount of indirection now, with little gain. Also the wsme serialization objects have been put in non-versioned location which is a step backwards.
I'd suggest:
- add a new binary (worker) that receives/processes olso messages
- send rpc messages directly from the API controller to the worker
- send the new nova objects rather than the API wsme objects (they are only for the API and should not leak out to the rest of the codebase)."}, {'account_id': 9094, 'date': '2013-12-17 18:55:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm going to work on a new patch to integrate the nova object model into the API code soon and I don't want to put everything into the controller. commit_message:
API worker architecture

-Introduced a handler class for encapsulating future DB layer work.
-Renamed solum/api/handlers/handler.py method put to update.
-Renamed solum/api/handlers/handler.py method post to create.
-Fixed tests to check for new status codes.
-Refactored a few commenets to use OpenStack recommended way.

Change-Id: I38fc94ff4cf6c1eb43f917b4fb2ed971929ddbf1

Add x-openstack-request-id to nova requests and responses

This makes use of the oslo middleware proposed in
change Ic7967cd6

(5 inline comments)

A few inline comments, and a few overall things:

There is an issue with the ThreadPool class included, so we will need to sync the updated version in, then rebase it on top of this changeset.

If you create a PTR record, and then do a list of all FIPs, or get a single FIP, it deletes the PTR record. Most likely an issue in central/service.py somewhere, but I haven't narrowed it down.

The zones should be created in a predefined tenent, not the calling users tenent.

Can you add some more logging? it makes it easier to see when calls have failed etc

We should only do actions if all neutrons return successfully,  as we don't want to hand out inconsistent data.
- Except in the case of 401's - we need to figure out what to do there

Preferably, in loops etc, can you make the variables more descriptive? trying to debug one char vars is painful :)"}, {'account_id': 395, 'date': '2014-01-12 21:21:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 25.'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-01-12 21:21:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 25:

commit_message:
FloatingIP PTR record functionality

* Central methods update_floatingip, get_floatingip, list_floatingip
* API according to
* https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Designate/Blueprints/Reverse
* Put network functionanlity into a pluggable api class (In case we want
* more)

blueprint floating-ip-ptrs

Change-Id: Ic9194e5bcfc8d25126b9e84652144f58cddcccfe

commit_message:
Turn block_device_mapping.volume_size to int

It was a string before, while it by its meaning should be an integer.
This change is backward compatible, as it still accepts string values.

Change-Id: I950bfbb1250f6aa63e9b20831cd92f1c9b974db2
Closes-Bug: #1267889

This change will remove the requested_project_id from being
included in the verification of the oauth signature when
issuing a request token.

The requested_project_id will still be required as a header,
when attempting to create a request token. But it should not be
included with the oauth specific headers.

Change-Id: I819a29119a359873633ab8fde553a11a8a37a682
'}]
commit_message:
Remove requested_project_id from oauth authorization parameters

This change will remove the requested_project_id from being
included in the verification of the oauth signature when
issuing a request token.

The requested_project_id will still be required as a header,
when attempting to create a request token. But it should not be
included with the oauth specific headers.

Change-Id: I819a29119a359873633ab8fde553a11a8a37a682

commit_message:
explicitly set rpc_backend in nova.conf

Implements: blueprint centos-rhel-for-compute
Fixes: bug #1269077

The following is a default value in openstack:

rpc_backend=nova.openstack.common.rpc.impl_kombu

Using RDO (rhel/centos) packages, this gets overridden in
/usr/share/nova/nova-dist.conf to 'impl_qpid'.

In order to cleanly set this back to the default value (which is what we
want as a default in the cookbooks), we need to explicitly set this in
nova.conf.

Change-Id: Idd025034c07ce12810a38eff87975b1c8caf1985

commit_message:
Fix incorrect capitalization in ceilometer install

According to the Conventions document, Ceilometer's official name is
OpenStack Telemetry, so the 'Telemetry Service' should be changed to
'Telemetry service' in install guide.

This patch only fixes the section_ceilometer-install.xml to make it
easier to review.

Change-Id: I1615c16660700dedd0be1eb460b83839142829be
ref: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions#Service_and_project_names
