The main thing i see this preventing is putting multiple filters on a revocation (i don't know if this is something we need).

Example

{ 'project': project_id, 'trust': trust_id }

Also the global scope here would just be to not provide any types.


The other things we discussed at summit is that the revocation list should be strictly ordered so that the most recent event is the first in the list. Also some way of requesting events from some event,"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-10 22:07:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Jamie: Need, no, but it will make it simpler to use.  We can have a generic "disable based on the scope of the type passed in" API as well, if it is really required, but I prefer the above.

Time ordering is tricky, as the need is to search by scope and Id.  However, fetching a Delta "all events after time X" does make sense.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-11 17:39:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-11 17:40:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-12-11 17:45:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-12-13 00:07:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

> I think I don't want to rely on the ordering of the events. Now allowing both project an user id on a token means that there are multiple keys that we'll have to check for revocation, and ideally we will optimize the search. I'd like to have the flexibility to reorder the list, and I am not willing to bank on JSON tools maintaining the order. Lets keep it based on the revocation time.

All of this optimization will/should happen client side though.

> I'm not willing to put a timestamp on the overall list, as that implies that the cache must update the timestamp on each request. Better for the client to maintain the time when it last requested the file, and to request all events after that timestamp.

No. It means that the cache must update the timestamp on the last entry that was added to the list which will be the same value as revoked_at. There are two time values here, the last time i called in and the last time something was revoked. I as a client want to provide you with something you gave me so i'll give you the last revoked_at i received, otherwise i have to deal with the possibility of clock differences.

I don't even care if it's not timestamp. If we save the last id added to the list that's ok. When i specify a ?since= i want to provide something that was given to me in the previous valid response and i will treat it as a blob.

I brought this up at summit which was where the ordering idea came from.

> Searching for the latest event is O(N) at worst case. I wouldn't optimize for that unless it is shown to be essential. Sorting on latest event is more expensive at O(N log(N) )

It's not really as time moves in one direction. revoked_at will always be increasing so all you need to do is strictly add new events to the start of the list. In the DB case you just request and index them with revoked_at DESC"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-13 18:25:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-13 18:30:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-12-14 15:21:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I realized that the scope of a revocation can't have an arbitrary number of values in it.  At most it can have is two:  one from the identity side,  one from the assignment side.  

Unless we loosen the rule that userid is unique, in which case we will need 2 values, but it still will be to uniquely identiy the user. In that case userid might be paired with idp_id. So the set of allowable values will be along the lines of:

userid
trustid
idpid

projectid 
domainid

userid, projectid
userid, domainid



If we go with a signing approach like the CMS Tokens, then we should probably use the same unique identifier to indicate what tokens to ignore.  This leads to some interesting questions of endpoint hierarchy:  is there any one endpoint that can revoke tokens for all other endpoints?  If an endpoint gets compromised, can it revoke all tokens everywhere?"}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-12-16 00:50:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

> I realized that the scope of a revocation can't have an arbitrary number of values in it. At most it can have is two: one from the identity side, one from the assignment side.

That's an implementation issue and not one that we should need to codify in the API. 

As for the rest I'm not following your argument.

Essentially revocation events should be able to match up to any data that is stored in the token. Whether user_id is global (yes) isn't relevant here and idp_id does not exist in the token. All that matters is that sufficient details go in to a revocation event to catch everything you need to revoke and if that includes passing domain_id with username or some other combination then so be it. 

As for dealing with endpoints, this API has nothing to do with cert management and revocation of certificates would need to be handled separately as this revoke check won't kick in until after the token has been decoded. 

Am i missing something?"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-23 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Add service_credentials for ceilometer-agent-central

ceilometer-agent-central will run interval_task which needs
basic config of service_credentials. However, current guide doesn't
provide such setting, so the task will fail and raise Unauthorized
exception.

This patch fixes this problem by adding sample config of
service_credentials section.

NOTE: This patch also fixes some content overflow problem in related
part.

Change-Id: I38b1d417c3aa1d7b31006045c01bc6cf759ed6d0
Closes-Bug: #1268866
(cherry picked from commit 93688b5133fcd003eeb046d5dfafebbc86ee5adb)

Upgrade cinder rootwrap config on havana to icehouse upgrade, so that it
switches to using oslo-rootwrap instead. This follows the model used by
Nova in previous upgrades.

Requires that configure_cinder_rootwrap() is available in devstack, so
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/65946 must land first.

Change-Id: Iccb262ac2005efdfb509edee7c967801d8fb0c65
'}]
commit_message:
Upgrade cinder rootwrap config on upgrade

Upgrade cinder rootwrap config on havana to icehouse upgrade, so that it
switches to using oslo-rootwrap instead. This follows the model used by
Nova in previous upgrades.

Requires that configure_cinder_rootwrap() is available in devstack, so
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/65946 must land first.

Change-Id: Iccb262ac2005efdfb509edee7c967801d8fb0c65

commit_message:
Clarify usage of an endpoint

Some debris were removed in this patch. The debris have been lost when
OSFT verification test was removed. This patch involves a clear endpoint
that represents an installation of OpenStack cluster. The current
format of an endpoint looks like that:

{
    "auth_url": "http://example.com:5000/v2.0",
    "username": "admin",
    "password": "secret",
    "tenant_name": "demo"
}

Each deploy engine should to return an endpoint as a result of
make_deploy method.

TODO: We can instantiate rally.osclients.Clients more simply such as
Clients(**endpoint).

Change-Id: Id5217714d08135b935e4594f931e04c7f04861c5

commit_message:
Enable $pybasedir value in pxe.py

We should not refer $pybasedir directly in our python code, because
it is loaded by paths.py, we should use paths.basedir_def("") to load
this $pybasedir value as a base path.

And change some 'nova' words to 'ironic in paths.py

Change-Id: I4c6bcb103d4d1eee8e7bf78f46c815630666cfe9
Closes-Bug: #1267351

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-10 20:44:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add new neutron-ovs-cleanup element.

This patch adds a new neutron-ovs-cleanup element which
configures the neutron-ovs-cleanup service to run
so that it cleans up *all* OVS ports. We want to do this
at a very specific time in the boot process so that DHCP
on reboot works properly:

 1) after OVS is available (nonetworking)
 2) before networking is started

Without this fix networking after rebooting an overcloud instance
is a total failure due to the fact that the physical NIC has been
moved to an OVS bridge by init-neutron-ovs and DHCP requests
fail.

The currently patch implements this on systemd only.

In addition to all the above, cleaning up old neutron ports is
a good idea on reboot anyways. So we get that for free here too.

Change-Id: Ic87f2388680ec4f67b6275b8d923f76b75559c78
Closes-bug: 1254533

commit_message:
Add new neutron-ovs-cleanup element.

This patch adds a new neutron-ovs-cleanup element which
configures the neutron-ovs-cleanup service to run
so that it cleans up *all* OVS ports. We want to do this
at a very specific time in the boot process so that DHCP
on reboot works properly:

 1) after OVS is available (nonetworking)
 2) before networking is started

NOTE: This service is not started on first boot but will
run on any subsequent reboots (it is enabled in os-refresh-config)

Without this fix networking after rebooting an overcloud instance
is a total failure due to the fact that the physical NIC has been
moved to an OVS bridge by init-neutron-ovs and DHCP requests
fail.

The currently patch implements this on systemd only.

In addition to all the above, cleaning up old neutron ports is
a good idea on reboot anyways. So we get that for free here too.

Change-Id: Ic87f2388680ec4f67b6275b8d923f76b75559c78
Closes-bug: 1254533

commit_message:
Network manager refactoring

Part 3.

1. Some cleaning in network manager.
2. A number of network manager tests added.
3. Some refactoring in NetworkConfigurationValidator and NetworkConfigurationVerifyHandlers.
4. Unification of network groups creation and of networks update.
5. Global parameters removed.

Implements: blueprint nailgun-network-manager-refactoring

Change-Id: I688174d4fc9fd3569696e03a8a3067e553d0ac9f

commit_message:
Use ironic.common.paths to get the templates paths

Instead of using the $pybasedir directly to get the pxe_config_template
and net_config_template options, this patch makes use of the
basedir_path() method from the ironic.common.paths modules to get the
uninterpolated paths relative to $pybasedir.

Change-Id: Ia940b4b46e743e03f0e5b957a247ded1bd9d68b7
Closes-Bug: #1269384

[{'created': '2013-12-13 15:04:41.000000000', 'message': 'LBaaS: synchronize haproxy deploy/undeploy_instance methods

When creating/deleting lbaas objects at a high rate (like tempest api tests do)
deploy/undeploy_unstance methods of haproxy namespace driver
may be executed concurrently which leads to different conflicts with
network namespaces and interfaces created by the diver.

@synchronized decorator should be used in order to ensure that only one thread
will execute one of the methods at a time.

Closes-Bug: #1260692

Change-Id: Ibe86653c20c9a4e0b4e7b3b2cefbd445428b82da
'}]
commit_message:
LBaaS: synchronize haproxy deploy/undeploy_instance methods

When creating/deleting lbaas objects at a high rate (like tempest api tests do)
deploy/undeploy_unstance methods of haproxy namespace driver
may be executed concurrently which leads to different conflicts with
network namespaces and interfaces created by the diver.

@synchronized decorator should be used in order to ensure that only one thread
will execute one of the methods at a time.

Closes-Bug: #1260692

Change-Id: Ibe86653c20c9a4e0b4e7b3b2cefbd445428b82da

commit_message:
Restart nova-compute after modify the config file

The Install the Compute agent for the Telemetry service section of
install-guide doesn't restart the nova-compute service after modify
/etc/nova/nova.conf file, so the configured option will not take
effect timely.

Change-Id: I8b4a14333c0d8d6e0a2633e7c3cf0997d2e46009
Closes-Bug: #1269198

Rename instance_type to flavor in hyper-v virt driver

Renames 'instance_type' to 'flavor' in the hyper-v virt driver and
associated tests.

Part of blueprint flavor-instance-type-dedup

tests: allow to skip if no database URL

This is needed for certain driver that we may not want to test if
there's no URL provided in the scenario, i.e. no environment variable
can be found.

commit_message:
Supports bash_completion for ceilometerclient

bash_completion feature can improve CLI user experience, projects like
nova, keystone, and cinder already support it.

NOTE: this patch just provides simple functionality, which means cache
for IDs and names is not used (like nova).

Change-Id: I1b04998a5e7c8818aed4b51f5fe5bf01efd0e14a
Closes-Bug: #1260939

commit_message:
cacert is not picked up correctly by alarm services

related to bug 1266472 which changes client to look only at os_cacert arg.
update alarm services to use just os_cacert as well.

Change-Id: Id28a0838330296fe030fa7c4a35a216dd3e64bad
Closes-Bug: #1266477

both Python 2 and 3.

In Python 2:

    >>> print(str(0.261666666666667))
    0.261666666667

In Python 3:

    0.261666666666667

Change-Id: I4beed7aff7e89f891024975b9df9208c987dc87c
'}]
commit_message:
Python 3: fix test_sample_list

Change the counter_volume field of "fake" samples to get compatibility with
both Python 2 and 3.

In Python 2:

    >>> print(str(0.261666666666667))
    0.261666666667

In Python 3:
    >>> print(str(0.261666666666667))
    0.261666666666667

[{'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:19:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:29:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't like the fact that we create a temp collection and later remove it. This seems a waste of time and space.

I think that we should try to change this method in such a way that we could keep reduced collection and use it later:

e.g. we do a map reduce on whole collection and in get_resource method we query collection that is already reduced. With such approach we won't have to do real time mapreduce.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:32:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think what you propose would work Alexei, but if you have a better solution, feel free to submit a patch."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:34:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Ok. lets get this one in to fix bug. 

I'll try to work on improvement in the next patch."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:36:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Code looks good. However, I'd like to mention a couple of things:

1) Map reduce in mongodb<2.4 runs in a single-threaded javascript engine. (Spidermonkey)
2) The aggregation framework uses indexes for sorting (if the fields are indexed). If the fields are not indexed, the issue will persist for map-reduce.
3) Map reduce writes to a temp collection. This has some performance impacts. I'd either recommend to reuse the data in that collection or write in a separate database to avoid hitting the DB lock (Which for your interest was moved down to a collection level in mongodb 2.6).

As a final note, it's always recommended to use the aggregation framework instead of map-reduce for 'live' operations. Map reduce is fine for batch operations that run 'once in a while'.

Hope this helps."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:42:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@fpercoco: thanks for the mongodb insight, though I think the performance issues you refer to are much more likely to impact on the statistics API (already MR-based and likely to be run much more often in real-time mode that the resource API).

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-01-10 14:47:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Sounds good!

I'd recommend migrating those endpoints to use the aggregation framework. Hope my comments helped!

Cheers,

[{'created': '2014-01-10 14:16:03.000000000', 'message': "Replace mongo aggregation with plain ol' map-reduce

Fixes bug 1262571

Previously, the mongodb storage driver an aggregation pipeline
over the meter collection in order to construct a list of resources
adorned with first & last sample timestamps etc.

However mongodb aggregation framework performs sorting in-memory,
in this case operating over a potentially very large collection.
It is also hardcoded to abort any sorts in an aggregation pipeline
that will consume more than 10% of physical memory, which is
observed in this case.

Now, we avoid the aggregation framework altogether and instead
use an equivalent map-reduce.

Change-Id: Ibef4a95acada411af385ff75ccb36c5724068b59
"}]
commit_message:
Replace mongo aggregation with plain ol' map-reduce

Fixes bug 1262571

Previously, the mongodb storage driver an aggregation pipeline
over the meter collection in order to construct a list of resources
adorned with first & last sample timestamps etc.

However mongodb aggregation framework performs sorting in-memory,
in this case operating over a potentially very large collection.
It is also hardcoded to abort any sorts in an aggregation pipeline
that will consume more than 10% of physical memory, which is
observed in this case.

Now, we avoid the aggregation framework altogether and instead
use an equivalent map-reduce.

Change-Id: Ibef4a95acada411af385ff75ccb36c5724068b59

commit_message:
Add service_credentials for ceilometer-agent-central

ceilometer-agent-central will run interval_task which needs
basic config of service_credentials. However, current guide doesn't
provide such setting, so the task will fail and raise Unauthorized
exception.

This patch fixes this problem by adding sample config of
service_credentials section.

NOTE: This patch also fixes some content overflow problem in related
part.

Change-Id: I38b1d417c3aa1d7b31006045c01bc6cf759ed6d0
Closes-Bug: #1268866

commit_message:
Add a note for ceilometer log_dir on Ubuntu

Currently, Ceilometer services on Ubuntu Precise have not been
launched with log_dir option, all the services except ceilometer-api
cannot generate their log files.

This patch adds a note for the log_dir option in case of such problem.

Change-Id: I324093df38854ca01038c99dad148bbca4c09e71
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1268541

commit_message:
Add to_dict() method to Resource class

Commit a07b8b0b introduces a regression when running 'heat
resource-show' command because heatclient.v1.resources.Resource class
didn't implement the to_dict() method.

This commit adds unit tests for resource show and list commands. It
also removes the use of MagicMock in these tests because it introduced
a recursion issue (see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/65269/).

Change-Id: I6c4c0e293d2955c67a0240136faa2721ef2e4ffa
Closes-Bug: 1266678

commit_message:
Change log from ERROR to WARNING when instance absent

Periodic task will update the host stat so that it will
collect all active instances and get their disk size
during the operation period, the instance might be resized
by nova operations, it will lead to disk file not exist
it's not an error from current design point of view, so
change from ERROR to WARNING to avoid confusion

Change-Id: I3b6f1416c248d9d4d2caaf2cc30a7c944685661c
Closes-Bug: #1243849

commit_message:
provide infrastructure for publishing docs to html

this brings over the pbr infrastructure for publishing rst files
to html with the oslo.sphix style. We'll need to move around
and reformat some of the documents for them to fully take effect
but this would be the first step in getting there.

Updated with our latest knowledge on how to do the right tox.ini
changes to handle sphinx issues.

This will then get used by another publish job to go to some
online repository.

Change-Id: I0dd3ecf0a9b3e356a4a2980a305b421b7d7b8602

[{'created': '2014-01-14 23:02:28.000000000', 'message': 'Refresh openstack-tools virtualenv every time

All of the commands there are idempotent. By not refreshing it, every
time we change this virtualenv initialization, such as the recent
addition of os-apply-config, we fail to build the virtualenv in the way
the rest of the code expects it to be built.

Change-Id: I07cefaf8348769cc7793936819175c1daaabd41b
'}]
commit_message:
Refresh openstack-tools virtualenv every time

All of the commands there are idempotent. By not refreshing it, every
time we change this virtualenv initialization, such as the recent
addition of os-apply-config, we fail to build the virtualenv in the way
the rest of the code expects it to be built.

Change-Id: I07cefaf8348769cc7793936819175c1daaabd41b

commit_message:
Do not require team diversity at incubation time

Remove the requirement for the development team to be "diverse" at
incubation time. Diversity is still a requirement for graduation.

Change-Id: I5ca509df9567b0fa7d6c99e67d4e6b7fb95d0659

commit_message:
Enabled Libvirt driver to read 'os_command_line' from image properties.

The os_command_line can now be presented to the Libvirt driver through the
glance image property 'os_command_line'.  When this property is present,
the driver uses its value instead of the default. Libvirt uses this
value as either kernel command line or arguments to init (in case of LXC).
DocImpact

bp: enable-libvirt-driver-to-read-kernel-command-line-from-glance-image
Change-Id: Iad53c687053bdb5469baad4331ea55f428c170b0

commit_message:
Add "ci_commands" ssh command filter

ci_commands is added to roots authorized_keys as
command="/usr/local/bin/ci_commands on the test hosts. And the
private key is being passed to the ci slaves. The slaves can now
use this key to ssh to the test environment and run a subset of
commands(filtered by ci_commands).

Change-Id: If08b81b8ff5ba6ce526406962e2c76097d141cf5
Co-Authored-by: Chris Jones <cmsj@tenshu.net>
Co-Authored-by: Robert Collins <rbtcollins@hp.com>

commit_message:
Let Integer property convert strings to numbers

This patch give backward compability in case changing
properties schema of resources.
Now property Integer may try convert string to integer.

Closes-bug: #1267924
Change-Id: I8eeb482e1d2bdbb4afa1378a3d751c206658f23a

commit_message:
Allow users to customize max header size

Also increases the default value from 8192 to 16384

The former max header (8192) is exceeded in the following scenario
- Auth tokens built with a keystone v3 API catalog
- A catalog with approximately 8 or more endpoints defined

Equivalent fixes have been proposed in other projects

Change-Id: Ic714166440e2aa08b619ab1e5e5e0cf3cea3e309
Closes-Bug: 1190149

just remove them.

commit_message:
Fix bug 1268456 for novaclient

For perviously logic, if flavor id is
start with "0Number", int(name_or_id)
will convert it to "Number". If flavor
id "Number" exist in DB, it will show
up for query with "0Number".
This fix enter flavor search logic at
the beginning. Also add one more UT
for this function.

Fixes: bug 1268456

Change-Id: I979ffcabd3d095eed1458bfcf4d608f951c88339

commit_message:
Move testtools to test-requirements.txt

The devstack-gate job is updated [1] to install packages from
test-requirements.txt. Hence move testtools from requirements.txt to
test-requirements.txt.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/64226

Change-Id: Ic3d3f4663bff64be91c23d9af46a3f766cbb7cf5

commit_message:
Add quota usage support for V2 API

This is the client support for nova quota-detail API extension. With
this new nova quota-usage command, it is possible for user to view not
only quota resource "limit" value, but also "in_use" and "reserved"
values.

Implements blueprint expose-quota-details

Change-Id: I3b0387417bb4fed9cb61baca319f4496e31af117

commit_message:
Changes path used for trove-guestagent.conf

Reasons:
- Guest Agent uses trove-guestagent.conf.sample directly,
  which is not correct way to do it.
- Probably this was a workaround, because /etc/trove-guestagent.conf
  was not building up due to another Bug: 1265184 in trove.

Changes:
- Corrected the path of config file to be used as
  /etc/trove-guestagent.conf.

Dependency:
- This change would only pass the gate-tests
  when Bug: 1265184 gets resolved.

Change-Id: I25ff15fb16ee80f33e447ff83ffa760919646446
Closes-Bug: #1176102

Andreas,

Yes, I'm removing python-novaclient, because it's a dependency of python-nova, which itself is a dependency of nova-common, which itself is a dependency of absolutely all Nova daemons. In other words, it's totally useless to explicitely install python-novaclient, it will be installed as part of the dependencies, and that's truth in both Debian and Ubuntu. So I'm removing it, to make it more simple.

If that's the reason of your -1, please fix it! :)

By the way, happy new year Andreas."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-01-07 13:49:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

    backport: havana
    Closes-Bug: #1252604

Please have a look at the bug and discussion - and if you remove it, state it in your commit message.

[{'created': '2014-01-07 12:12:23.000000000', 'message': "Fix controller howto for Debian

Many parts of the install-guide for the nova controler node
and compute node must be removed in Debian, since that's
handled by Debconf. It is more confusing than anything else.
So this patch hides some steps from the Debian install-guide.

Change-Id: I374cf3fb3103b49c60f28648e1f7a16dfe274387
"}]
commit_message:
Fix controller howto for Debian

Many parts of the install-guide for the nova controler node
and compute node must be removed in Debian, since that's
handled by Debconf. It is more confusing than anything else.
So this patch hides some steps from the Debian install-guide.

Change-Id: I374cf3fb3103b49c60f28648e1f7a16dfe274387

'}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2014-01-02 19:05:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The code looks good, but if this is a regression in Havana, is there an alternative fix that doesn't add a config option and a db migration? These are very difficult to backport.

Also, I thought the extra-specs matching was supposed to be matching against host aggregates, so I'm not sure why we need a new db column and flag?"}, {'account_id': 221, 'date': '2014-01-06 16:37:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Vish, thanks for commenting!

The fundamental difference is that host_aggregates uses AggregateInstanceExtraSpecsFilter, while extra_specs uses ComputeCapabilitiesFilter.
And the value of extra_specs can be dynamically changed by compute node, but host_aggregate is static.
Before Havana, the capabilities data was broadcast over RPC.
However, in Havana, we can't access host_state.host information any more w/o using db
after making compute_capabilities_filter directly use the data in host_state (by Joe Gordon).
Since Havana, extra_spec info is not stored in the db, and host_state.host information does not have extra_spec info.

This code patches are to fix Icehouse/upstream bug about extra_specs.

To fix Havana release (backport) w/o changing db and config option, we can think of the following options, but
any better idea is welcome.

(1) Use extra_resources db column b/c it was added but not used in Havana release and use the same flavor_extra_specs flag in baremetal config section. But, for Icehouse release, we need to add separate db column b/c extra_resources will be used for other purpose (resource_tracker) and need to add new config option before baremetal is fully replaced by Ironic.
(2) Revert to RPC scheme for extra_specs. But, it's very big changes and we know that it's against OpenStack milestones.
(3) No extra_spec bug fix for Havana release --> bug fix for only upstream/Icehouse."}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2014-01-06 19:02:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

While the config option theoretically allowed for dynamically changing the extra specs reported by the node, I am not aware of anything actually using it. AFAIK, to change the extra specs you had to change the config option and restart nova compute which is an annoying admin task. It is much easier to modify the host aggregate metadata because you can actually do it through an api.

Please let me know if I have missed something or if there is a real use case that needs the config option version.

In my mind a better solution to all of this would be to deprecate instance_type_extra_specs. Since fixing it properly in havana is so complex, we could just declare bankruptcy and make a known issue for havana and add some release notes for havana telling people they have to convert their config options to host aggregates.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-01-06 19:03:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with Vish"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-01-07 16:48:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Do not merge

Yeah, I think we should just deprecate it and list it as a known issue on https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/Havana'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-15 06:03:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Adding support for extra_specs (key:value pairs)

After changing compute_capabilities_filter from RPC to DB,
instance_type_extra_specs doesn't work at all.
This bug is fixed by adding extra_specs column into compute_nodes
and comparing each key:value pair between flavor_extra_specs
in nova.conf and flavor-key.

Change-Id: I558c42e1be1fb58c9c23fdfb056de472be84c26b
Closes-Bug: #1245541
Co-authored-by: David Kang <dkang@isi.edu>

It feels wrong, but it's consistent with the other admin-only properties we've added lately :)"}, {'account_id': 7761, 'date': '2014-01-04 06:49:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-01-04 08:19:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

What does "administrative users" mean?

Every request should be scoped to a tenant, explicitly via the token scoping, that is what's validated with keystone, and what sets the tenant in the request context.

So I don't understand why we would ever want to allow a request to create resources in a tenant other than that specified in the request context.

I see this has been discussed somewhat in bug #1246629, but I believe this (and probably the neutron api?) is perpetuating the wrong assumption (that is a keystone bug, ref bug #968696) that admin role is global - it is not, and no such concept of a "global admin" exists in keystone - admin role assignment is per tenant.

So I think at least this needs futher discussion - maybe the issue is the neutron API is broken, I'm not sure, but adding tenant_id to any resource seems wrong to me - everything (other than the management-api stuff, which I'm also uncomfortable with) should always be scoped to the context tenant/project.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-01-04 08:50:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Do not merge

Actually, sorry Zane but -2 - this is wrong and we need to discuss it properly to avoid merging a bunch of stuff which will turn into security holes when the keystone admin scoping bug gets fixed.

The whole admin only property thing seems wrong, but I guess it's acceptable if there are some resource capabilities only available to project admins.  

But anything which allows the resource interface to defeat the request scoping is just wrong IMO and we shouldn't be doing it (we should be banishing tenant ID from all request bodies and the path, so we can solely rely on the keystone derived context, so we avoid any more stuff like bug #1256983 happening)"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-01-06 15:39:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

> What does "administrative users" mean?

My understanding was that it means whatever Neutron's policy.json says it means ;)

I really don't like these admin-only properties, and I would really like to be able to hide them from the average user while still making them available to things like TripleO. But for now it seems that we already crossed this bridge.

From IRC discussion it sounds like you think the Neutron API will have to change in the near future, and therefore we shouldn't attempt to model it yet. I guess my reasoning is that only the policy and not the API should need to change. In any event, dropping my review to +1 so that discussion can happen.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-01-06 15:50:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

> From IRC discussion it sounds like you think the Neutron API > will have to change in the near future

Well that is my argument, yes - neutron is making assumptions in the policy and API which probably will not be true when bug #968696 is fixed.

All roles other than admin are scoped to a project/tenant, so having projects which rely on admin role assignment having global scope is broken, and we shouldn't perpetuate that brokenness by exposing the tenant_id in the resource properties - we already have the tenant_id, it's in the context.

It may be that some keystone functionality is required to support the use-case where one token is expected to enable authorization on multiple projects/tenants, but I'm not aware of what that functionality is atm."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-01-06 17:58:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

OK, so after talking to Clint on IRC, it turns out that I misunderstood and this is not something that TripleO are using or would be likely to use. So I'm setting -1 pending some explanation of why the Neutron API actually makes sense, because it is different from every single other API in OpenStack in allowing you to create something in a different tenant from where you are authenticated. At least on the face of it that concept as insane, and while there may be a good justification for it, none has been advanced so far."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-01-07 14:11:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Further info, see these:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/61869/

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/keystone/+spec/service-scoped-tokens

Specifically this bit from the BP:

"As a side effect, an "admin" assignment on a project would no longer convey global "admin"ness. This wouldn't break existing deployments unless they also use revised authorization policies which take advantage of the new attributes."

IOW, don't do what neutron is doing from now on.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-15 06:03:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-15 06:03:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Added tenant_id property to OS::Neutron::Router

Now a router could be created passing the ID of the tenant which will
own the router. Only administrative users can set the tenant
identifier.

Some test were added to ensure that tenant_id is handled properly, and
some of the existing test were reorganized in different classes.

Change-Id: If47f89577673a98c0b6332db3a16a829f667c574
Closes-Bug: #1246629

commit_message:
l3_agent: use spawn instead of spawn_n in _process_routers

spawn_n returns a greenlet object from which it is not possible to
retrieve either a return value or whether it raised any exceptions.
spawn returns a GreenThread object which you can use to get the
results of the call. In order to let the caller know the failure of
processing router(s), we should use spawn insead of spawn_n.

Added a new exception named ProcessRoutersError that is raised if
the spawned function fails.
Added related unit tests.

Change-Id: I15b732c97d52c74c15b08961bf01f6dca4e19a59
Closes-Bug: #1254984
Co-Authored-By: Hirofumi Ichihara <ichihara.hirofumi@lab.ntt.co.jp>

commit_message:
Set SCSI as default disk bus on Power KVM

Overwrites the default KVM bus for disk and cdrom, IDE and virtio,
respectively. This check (after the get_disk_bus_for_device_type
call) keeps the current code flow for other archs and virt types.

Change-Id: I5098001180b3a87b4b5dfc84f9671d976c6248c6

commit_message:
Change l3-agent to periodically check children are running

The l3-agent will now store info on the metadata-proxy process
it spawns, and use it to check if it's still running every time
_sync_routers_task() is called.  If it is not alive it will be
restarted.

A new flag, called 'check_child_processes', controls this behaviour.
Default value is False.

Closes-Bug: #1257775

Change-Id: Icc304db31b4a5cca292f52d82d3eb80383a54918

commit_message:
Fixes delete of protected rbd images

This fixes the scenario where an rbd-backed glance image is
deleted when the underlying rbd image has a protected snapshot
because a clone exists in cinder i.e. a volume that has been
created (cloned) from the image currently exists. The solution
here is to flag the rbd image for async delete, allow the
glance delete to succeed and check on some future event
(currently on subsequent deletes) whether the image is able to
be deleted and attempt a cleanup.

Closes-bug: bug 1185851
Change-Id: I3e0a08d392b90be6a544eeb841b7a1205b7c8cca

commit_message:
Except 404 for "detail" api call of deleted flavor

* Nova (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59860/) will not return details
  of deleted flavor for flavor detail api because deleted/non-deleted
  flavorid are not unique in DB, and duplicate flavor of same flavorid
  can be returned by flavor details api
* Fix the related tempest test to expect 404 for detail flavor api call
* Skip the test till Nova review gets in
  (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59860/)

Change-Id: I1695fb827d65feea119a76aac4c393b60b866a4e
Closes-Bug: #1153926

I want to understand the doc impact here. A couple of questions:
- How is deployment of nova affected? Which lines of api-paste.ini will change, for example?
- Does this limit an operator from choosing to run v2 Compute API instead of v3? (I don't think it does but configuration isn't clear to me from looking here.)
- Will the documentation of v3 API happen from pecan (once all extensions are rewritten)?"}, {'account_id': 8005, 'date': '2013-12-18 05:04:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

My Nova knowledge is probably more limited than others on this review, but here's my take.  Others, feel free to correct me:

1.  Deployment shouldn't be affected, as this iteration still calls for using paste under the hood for serving the API(s).  The only thing that's changing here is the actual WSGI app that paste will serve (which is based on pecan)

2.  This doesn't limit an operator from running v2 vs. v3.  The goal here is an alternative implementation of v3 endpoints based on pecan.

3.  I'm unsure about documentation because I'm not totally sure how it works in Nova right now :).  I think this would probably involve changing the current documentation generation to properly handle these pecan-based extensions.  This is something we should get working *as we translate*, not just hoping it all comes together at the end.  Can anybody chime in on how this *currently* works?  Is it something that should be addressed in this patch or in a follow-up?"}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2013-12-18 05:58:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The difficulty is that the API doesn't have much breadth, but is quite deep when you consider extensions.  As you know, its composition can really be quite complicated. '}, {'created': '2013-12-11 02:25:44.000000000', 'message': "Add the ability to define API extensions using pecan

This is a potential approach I've considered for gradually moving the V3 API
to pecan.  Other newer projects tend to define their API declaratively with
pecan's object dispatch-style routing, but given Nova's large number of
extensions (and the fact that API routing is a composition of installed
packages with stevedore entrypoints), this would probably involve a complete
rewrite of v3.  Instead, this approach entails:

1.  Creating a pecan WSGI app that auto-discovers extensions written with pecan
2.  Overwrides the /v3/ WSGI app's __call__ to attempt to route to the pecan
    app *first*, falling back to the previous WSGI implementation if no
    matching pecan controller is found
3.  Extensions are gradually rewritten using pecan.  This patchset provides an
    implementation of the `version` endpoint.  When all extensions make
    use of pecan, the previous WSGI routing code is removed

Includes support for using our existing XML and ATOM serialization functions.

Implements: blueprint v3-api-pecan
Change-Id: I6f2b62228c4dcae704f5768bca2fbdac5afc54ee

commit_message:
Add the ability to define API extensions using pecan

This is a potential approach I've considered for gradually moving the V3 API
to pecan.  Other newer projects tend to define their API declaratively with
pecan's object dispatch-style routing, but given Nova's large number of
extensions (and the fact that API routing is a composition of installed
packages with stevedore entrypoints), the more traditional approach would
probably involve a fundamental change in how the API is structured/composed.
Instead, this approach entails:

1.  Creating a pecan WSGI app that auto-discovers extensions written with pecan
2.  Overrides the /v3/ WSGI app's __call__ to attempt to route to the previous
    WSGI implementation *first*, falling back to the pecan implementation if no
    matching route is found
3.  Gradually rewriting extensions using pecan.  This patchset provides an
    implementation of the `version` endpoint.  When all extensions make
    use of pecan, the previous WSGI routing code is removed

Includes support for using our existing XML and ATOM serialization functions.

Implements: blueprint v3-api-pecan
Change-Id: I6f2b62228c4dcae704f5768bca2fbdac5afc54ee

commit_message:
Handle dict in object serialization

object doesn't handle dict serialization. For instance,
serializing {'foo': 123, 'obj': MyObj()} would cause an error.

The case will happen in filter_properties which is going to contain
instance type objects.
This patch is to add that support.

As remotable_classmethod() does, because deserialize_entity()
will convert primitives of Nova objects in 'updates' in
remotable() to real Nova objects, where 'updates' is also a
dict. We don't need to convert it again if a Nova object is
one of the fields.

Related to blueprint icehouse-objects.

Change-Id: I754bd33adc48cbd2279e0b914e9a3d399dca3c8a

commit_message:
For function "find_resource", should firstly handle falvor id.

	    For perviously logic, if flavor id is start with "0Number", int(name_or_id) will convert it to "Number". If flavor id "Number" exist in DB, it will a
	    This fix enter flavor search logic at the beginning. Also add one more UT for this function.

	    Fix bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-novaclient/+bug/1268456
Change-Id: I015d7a7f5c07980c0e5f4ed03fdc8d189cadabb7

commit_message:
Only add ceilometer user to nova group if using compute agent

When using ceilometer outside of the compute context (ex: with the
swift middleware), puppet-ceilometer attempts to add the user to
the nova group which does not (and probably should not) exist on
the swift nodes.

Change-Id: I6cc68152325a967c024ce611f92a90ce0afba8cc
(cherry picked from commit d064997cd4c50d9b5365fe2ffca60e14a86b08e1)

commit_message:
Remove "Delete" buttons when VPN objects are in use

Deleting attached services and policies doesn't
cause NotImplementedError anymore. Moreover,
options "Delete VPN Service", "Delete IKE Policy" and
"Delete IPSec Policy" don't appear in corresponding row
if there is a connection created using these objects.
Some tests are added to detect such errors in future.

Fixes bug 1252330

Change-Id: I9ed1b4ecdad54b89bef45b2f5e422c30447cceb5

commit_message:
Improve docs about horizon settings

added ALLOWED_HOSTS
added SESSION_TIMEOUT

Since settings become longer and longer, I re-arranged the options
in alphabetical order.

Change-Id: I4424cc178ec0cd7892b0f07cb0192b5af5b2ee0d
Partial-bug: #1221115

[{'created': '2013-12-10 09:18:39.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Adding testenv work wrapper script

Adding this now as a WIP to show the direction its going in(and to get feedback),
all of the TODO's need to be fixed before its is merged for real.

As is I havn't tested it but will be improving on it ASAP.

Change-Id: I46b2c95ccbda484b4de03585b830ac578df0e937
"}, {'created': '2013-12-10 16:31:12.000000000', 'message': "Adding testenv worker wrapper script

Adds a script 50-setup-testenvs which is run by os-refresh-config on
first boot. This carves up the host into a number of test environments
and starts a gearman worker for each environment. Each test environment
will have a seed, 3 vm's all on their own bridge.

Change-Id: I46b2c95ccbda484b4de03585b830ac578df0e937

commit_message:
Adding testenv worker wrapper script

Adds a script 60-setup-testenvs which is run by os-refresh-config. On
first boot this carves up the host into a number of test environments
and starts a gearman worker for each environment, noop if run more
than once. Each test environment will have a seed, 3 vm's all on
their own bridge.

Depends-on: Ie33736850ec8186f0c90b82b6fbb0fd57fe47dc9
Change-Id: I46b2c95ccbda484b4de03585b830ac578df0e937

Use wait condition when waiting for undercloud

We can now use the Heat stack wait condition to determine that the
undercloud node is up and fully initialized.

commit_message:
Move devstack hooks from infra config to solum repo

To minimize the work done in infra project and reduce the dependency, let us
have the code in solum repository and invoke the same from devstack job.

Change-Id: I910aa8ae6f9b4083952ca27d9f3c6807532ef784

"}]
commit_message:
Exceptions cleanup

Most TaskFlow exception don't have 'Exception' suffix in their names, so
we drop it from the few that have it, for sake of consistency and more
concise and expressive code.

MissingDependencies parent object is changed from InvalidState to
InvariantViolation, which is more appropriate.

Unused ClosedException is dropped.

Breaking change: any client code that used renamed exceptions,
ClosedException or relied on catching MissingDependencies as
InvariantViolationException is affected.

Change-Id: I649b7760d382ccb6df333bdffd667ba6b67a431e

commit_message:
rubocop compliance

all cops now pass except for the following
(which are silenced in .rubocop.yml )

* LineLength, MethodLength: not sure if we care about these
* WordArray: I prefer [] vs %w{} for readability.

Conflicts:
	metadata.rb
	recipes/common.rb
	recipes/openvswitch.rb
	spec/openvswitch_spec.rb

Change-Id: I92996b5db9f292e9ba93c7619ca727ffa92ddd71

commit_message:
Implement Rubocop

Per the blueprint, finish implementing rubocop across the entire
cookbook, remove tailor references, and update rubocop dependency.

- Update Chef Dependency to 11.8
- Add .rubocop.yml files to resources/providers
- Add resources/providers to Strainerfile
- Update all files necessary to pass rubocop

commit_message:
Add API binding options

Ceilometer is able to bind API server to both an IP address and a port.
This patch aims to add support for both configuration flags.

Change-Id: I83164a925cf115d091cb04d14922ee7bbdd0ac63
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit f8eea90cd9f1652ba927bfcc9bf8234af8983c11)

commit_message:
Removed packages installed as dependencies by OVS plug-in agent

I removed packages installed as dependencies by the Open vSwitch
plug-in agent package on Ubuntu and Debian. For example, the
neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent package automatically installs
the openvswitch-switch package, so the instructions shouldn't
specifically call out installing the latter.

Also, on the controller node which doesn't need to run the OVS
plug-in agent but still needs to know about the configured plug-in,
I changed the neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent package to the
neutron-plugin-openvswitch package.

Change-Id: I13a50854149109a10155d0b6b05307a663563438
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1264184
(cherry picked from commit 6931ad585b0392bdd118e6a40258caa5887ffd9d)

commit_message:
Replace oslo.uuidutils module with trove.utils

Oslo is removing uuidutils during the icehouse cycle.
Consequently we need to remove all references to uuidutils, and
replace them with the corresponding function from trove.utils.

Change-Id: Idd4b25e98624dfb6a25e275cac44a54324f50449
Closes-bug: 1253497

Updates oslo.context

This change is needed for uuidutils removal in Trove

13eb01c Adding domain to context and log
12bcdb7 Remove vim header
bdabd51 Remove uuidutils imports in oslo modules

Change-Id: I3b4eead93fc2d12ccb6a0837f9100b784b25d8dd

commit_message:
Relocates generate_random_password to common.utils

Reasons:
- instance.models._create_resources is still uses uuid as root_password.
- generate_random_password needs to be used in a diferent module, so it
  is a candidate to be moved to trove.common.utils, so that any
  new change could be made at one place only, affecting all used-cases.

Changes:
- Relocates generate_random_password to common.utils
- Replaces uuidutils.generate_uuid with generate_random_password in
  trove.instance.models._create_resources(password_length).

Change-Id: Ib58bf83b3c052261418907db41ca963768d2e710
Closes-Bug: #1264330

commit_message:
Fix broken iptables command in cinder

Fixes a broken iptables command from
3f34fc4d287fcd2ed7a1be9e116c85a8d336b19e.

This was causing invalid port/service errors.

Also, fixes an issue where the /var/run/cinder
directory doesn't actually exist.

With both of these fixes the cinder element
actually runs for me.

Change-Id: I236a84ac7c73b0295d4734fac62f94b9722bd512
Closes-bug: 1269143

commit_message:
Replace calls to pyudev with calls to a fake pyudev when not available

When running tox on platforms that do not have pyudev, tox exits with an
error due to the import error.

See http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-January/023268.html

Change-Id: I94de089ea0b661f62dedecd9977379adb56def6b

commit_message:
Improve testing of list_extensions for compute

This commit takes the testing for list_extension from the volumes
extensions client and uses it for the compute testing of
list_extensions. This also fixes a skip decorator to use use
requires_ext instead of calling is_extension_enabled directly.

Change-Id: Id08f39e09df0aea0d3c8f507f421c82ddf32900f

commit_message:
JobExecutionsManager.create() should handle input_id/output_id == None

Input and output ids are not part of the Java workflow JSON schema. Including
them, even set to None, causes an error.  In order to maintain backward
compatibility, leave input_id and output_id as required parameters but
do not add them to the job exec data if they are None.

Closes-Bug: #1268695
Change-Id: I8df8cb86094f5d67ca16de7d6dd253af142eca25

To catch some remarks, ideas'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-12-03 14:49:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I just took a very quick look at this patch, and really like the idea of allowing an L3 agent to handle all external networks. I've never seen the point in limiting or specifying the external networks, other than to allow use with a single external network bridge. But external networks can be accessed as provider networks rather than the external bridge, in which case there is no need for this limitation.

You may need to consider making sure external_network_bridge is unset when multiple (or all) external networks are enabled.

Also, I'm wondering if there is really a need for an explicit list of multiple external networks, or if selection between a single one or allowing all (setting the existing gateway_external_network_id to *) is sufficient?

Finally, is any enhancement of agent scheduling needed to take advantage of this? 

Given the ML2 plugin's ability to support heterogeneous network topologies, there could be situations where not all L3 agents could bind to all external networks. I'm wondering if the agent scheduler could somehow ask the agents to try to bind to the external networks. Maybe the gateway_external_network_ids list in config is sufficient for this, but it would be great if there was a more automatic, or at least API-driven, way to manage the agents' connectivity to external networks."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2013-12-03 15:57:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Robert,

Thanks for your response :)

Do you think that I should report this as a bug for this patch or a blueprint ?

Thanks for pointing the external_network_bridge stuff.

I added an extra param in order to have more flexibility of configuration, like this we are able to address more use cases IMHO.

If this patch/approach makes sense I will also rework the agent scheduler part, maybe on top of this patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52884/.

I sent an email to the ML to get more inputs.

I'm not very sold by the external network l3 binding. I think It could be better to bind a l3 agent according to an external network by its CIDR or as you said by the l3 API. thus same question, do I have to write a BP ? 

Regards,

Sylvain"}, {'account_id': 2874, 'date': '2013-12-04 03:22:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

external network bridge is a legacy when we don't support provider network. now we can easily have one l3 agent supports all external networks by external_network_bridge set to nothing i.e. external_network_bridge=.
By set to nothing, the qg-xxxxx interfaces will be plugged into br-int, and external network traffic will go the way like normal tenant network does.

'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-01-07 11:01:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Some pedantry in comments.

One last question I have, and this is just for discussing as I've got no strong opinion, is about the fact that external_network_bridge and external_network_gateway_id are not independent.

This means that the behaviour of the agent wrt external_network_gateway_id actually depends on the value of external_network_bridge; the case in which one would expect multiple networks to be supported because external_network_gateway_id is none and instead only one will be supported because the bridge is for instance set to br-ex will probably be fairly common.

I wonder if there's any possibility to support multiple external networks on any bridge, or to do something in order to ensure the intention is clear and otherwise fail at startup."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2014-01-07 13:19:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think you should also update L3AgentSchedulerDbMixin.get_l3_agent_candidates() to let it return agents which support multiple external networks (in case routers 'external_gateway_info' is set)."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-07 17:35:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

@Salvatore

IHMO, the only way for a l3 agent to be able to handle any networks is to use the provider networks and the parameter bridge_mappings. Without that, br-ex is limited to one network, and don't see how we could raise an exception at startup, since at startup one can have only one network and create a new one after ? BTW I'm not very sold on the usage of the gateway_external_network_id, not easy to manage it with the deployment automation tools. Maybe we could improve all these things, but I think this is not the goal of this patch.

@Oleg
Thanks for the review, I will check that."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-07 22:40:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: (1 inline comment)

Oleg the L3AgentSchedulerDbMixin.get_l3_agent_candidates() method seems to be ok. It returns the agents if there is no gateway_external_network_id and doesn't use the external_network_bridge to filter the agents. Also the agents in the unit tests of the test_l3_schedulers.py file are configured without these two parameters and are returned by the get_l3_agent_candidates method."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-07 22:41:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-01-08 01:11:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
L3 Agent can handle many external networks

With this patch a l3 agent can handle
any networks by setting the neutron
parameter external_network_bridge
and gateway_external_network_id to
empty.

Related-Bug: #1234750
Related-Bug: #1194350

Change-Id: Id260a239df23951da730513f40cda490002effc3

commit_message:
Added cache for image_username

This change removes roundtrip to nova for each remote() call.

It is also important for long provision operations because auth
token could expire during cluster provisioning timeframe.

Introduced nodegroup.image_username field with information about
username used.

Change-Id: I00f318a9bf34b221c8ccf7a4f22e9ed3fd91e806

commit_message:
Fix WADL validation errors

The dbaas.wadl file contains many text blocks which need to be
wrapped in <para> tags. Newer versions of clouddocs-maven-plugin
validate these blocks, resulting in docs build errors until they are
fixed.

Co-Authored-By: Nikhil Manchanda <SlickNik@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ia5733a7fb1c0827a7cec500e1ee51a896a0e7754

commit_message:
checking for metaclass to be Python 3.x compatible

The way to using metaclass has changed in Python3.(H236)

Python 2.7 way:

class Foo(object):
  __metaclass__ = FooMeta

Python 3 way:

class Foo(object, metaclass=FooMeta):
  ...

The six.add_metaclass() decorator allows us to use one syntax that
works for both Python 2.7 and Python 3.

Change-Id: I24a00d9e59ffdd9abf4ccf3919737bdb079819eb
Related-Bug: #1236648

commit_message:
Add finer granularity to host aggregate APIs

This change provides the ability to set finer permission rules around
the host aggregate APIs. Prior to this change, all operations assumed
that the same permissions were necessary. However, it's very possible
that an OpenStack administrator may want to have varying sets of
permissions for operations across the standard CRUD operations.  This
change is only applicable to the v3 APIs as v2 APIs should remain
backwards compatible.

Also included is a change to fake_policy.py (since the file was
updated anyway) to make the base aggregate policy require the
'admin_api' rule (i.e., to be consistent with the policy.json file).

Also added the corresponding API test cases.

DocImpact v3 host aggregate APIs require action-level policies
Implements: blueprint aggregate-api-policy

Change-Id: I8a88824bbb41807fad849ad15af4411d3a3dca6e

commit_message:
Add filter and pagination to stack_get_all

This change prepares the ground for calls that are not tenant-scoped
to make use of the filter and paging capabilities.

Implements: blueprint management-api
Change-Id: I4862752999629666b46da20c2713edc950c5d52e

commit_message:
port admin/test_servers* into Nova V3 tests part2

1. porting admin/test_servers.py and admin/test_servers_negative.py
   into nova v3
2. sync nova v2 changes in Ibd04a1fdaab74fe59bcf16cc99d4ecf4821f4ae2
3. fix a few typos in servers_client.py

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I319bef11d1aee11ffa892c366cd57eef338b36ee
Closes-Bug: #1259056

commit_message:
Remove copyright from empty files

According to policy change in HACKING:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#openstack-licensing
empty files should no longer contain copyright notices.

Closes-Bug: #1262424

commit_message:
Remove PostgreSQL dependencies from Barbican.

PostgreSQL is an optional database type for use with Barbican, so there
is no need to include that as a forced dependency on Barbican.

Change-Id: I260ce85475b83079d173ad57f3e755efd1841483

commit_message:
Isolated network support

This patch aims to enable support for both:
- isolated metadata which enable metadata support on isolated networks.
- metadata networks which allows for serving metadata requests coming
  from a dedicated metadata access network

Change-Id: I0e892c4183bd2bf1910b9b6758c1759475053529
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
removing run_tests.sh

run_tests.sh is a shell script that builds a virtualenv, runs
setup.py, and executes tests.  This file is not used by the
build process or by developers.  Tox is being used for this
functionality.

Change-Id: Ib86cdc98052154b9f5b40f09f9786a827a754792

commit_message:
Remove __MARCONI_SETUP__

The built-in Marconi used to use to track the service bootstrap process,
is not needed anymore. This patch removes it.

Change-Id: Ia599bd07006306a5b6368d52cd8548cb50b3d01e

The ubuntu packages for nova-compute-kvm still drop the config file /etc/nova/nova-compute.conf that contains the following:

[DEFAULT]
libvirt_type=kvm
compute_driver=libvirt.LibvirtDriver

Additionally nova-compute is launched with command line options for both /etc/nova/nova.conf and /etc/nova/nova-compute.conf in that order.  It is my understanding that the later config file options will overwrite config options from /etc/nova/nova.conf.  In that case if you change the virt type but have an older package installed the virt type will not get set to the one that you intended.

The better solution would be to move everything to conf.d style config files which AFAIK is supported in havana via oslo but that is going to require the upstream packagers to get on board."}, {'account_id': 7769, 'date': '2014-01-14 14:48:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-14 14:03:43.000000000', 'message': "Avoid echoing comment from makefile recipe

We include a comment to explain why nova-compute-instance.yaml is
included in the prerequisite list for overcloud.yaml, but this comment
gets echoed by make before it executes the recipe using a shell.

  $> make overcloud.yaml
  # overcloud-source.yaml [..] won't work here because [..]
  # a prerequisite but don't want to pass it into merge.py
  python ./tripleo_heat_merge/merge.py overcloud-source.yaml [..]
  mv overcloud.yaml.tmp overcloud.yaml

Instead, maintain a list of files included by overcloud.yaml in a
variable and put a comment above that.

Change-Id: I1af69fbb33e1833170f086aec9b54c5c4e57138f
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid echoing comment from makefile recipe

We include a comment to explain why nova-compute-instance.yaml is
included in the prerequisite list for overcloud.yaml, but this comment
gets echoed by make before it executes the recipe using a shell.

  $> make overcloud.yaml
  # overcloud-source.yaml [..] won't work here because [..]
  # a prerequisite but don't want to pass it into merge.py
  python ./tripleo_heat_merge/merge.py overcloud-source.yaml [..]
  mv overcloud.yaml.tmp overcloud.yaml

Instead, maintain a list of files included by overcloud.yaml in a
variable and put a comment above that.

Change-Id: I1af69fbb33e1833170f086aec9b54c5c4e57138f

commit_message:
Step 1 refactoring Mistral engines

 * Action definition was combined in actions module
 * workflow from both single and scalable engines were deleted
 * task from single engine was deleted
 * unit test 'test_workflow' was deleted due to deleting workflow
 * minor fixes to single engine

 Next step will be extracting and combining common parts
 of scalable and single engine.

Change-Id: I15fbbb7f9d5e453c17625423eeb1bf841a19db18

commit_message:
Initial rubocop support for attributes/*.rb

Keeping in accordance with the other projects, adding a few standard
settings for rubocop. Dont check line lengths and dont suggest word arrays
for attributes files.

Addresses: blueprint rubocop-for-identity
Change-Id: I68728d2b9f73362fb4333c34dd6ed611efb4e7af

commit_message:
Updates cinder element

The previous cinder element was lacking a notty file and didn't
open the required ports in iptables.  This patch also allows a
developer to install the minimum required components for a
single cinder instance or (n) cinder-volume nodes.

This update results in 3 elements
cinder        : common cinder element
cinder-api    : installs the cinder api and scheduler
cinder-volume : installs the cinder volume service

Change-Id: I1ed9f67848be5716135085b6eaebc1f381ad83f9

commit_message:
Remove redundant user ownership declaration and ensure spec test coherency

swift is already set as a owner for File[] resources. This is a
simple cleanup that removes a redundant user declaration. The spec
tests did not verify that default File[] values were applied to
/var/lib/swift.

Change-Id: I608ef39ca8bbf78ca8029a65979db659184baa3f

This patchs aims to deprecate the param and raise a warning when using
it.

commit_message:
Update GlusterFS driver

Since https://github.com/openstack/cinder/commit/e997f8b06ecd4ed0a13c557d621db69eb68f2f3d
got merged, glusterfs_disk_util is now removed.
This patchs aims to raise an error when using it.

Change-Id: Ic5b9b0a742482d6b7380cb59fbec6b490a206779
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
L3 schedulers support

Icehouse brings new schedulers for virtual routing.
This patch aims to:
- add router_scheduler_driver flag support
- document which schedulers we could use

Change-Id: I9ed4464201e1b888ae7474221babe8e5aad38642
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Support network_device_mtu of nova managed interfaces

network_device_mtu configure the MTU for nova managed network interfaces.
By default no specific network_device_mtu configuration is set. The
interface defaults will be used as they got created.

This options allows configuration of Jumbo Frame usage.

Change-Id: Ia391f3daa788c780c4492071a480052b4ef4cc37

commit_message:
Sync glossary and firstterm

Ensure that for each firstterm, we have a proper entry in the glossary:
* Use <firstterm baseform="xxx"> if the first term is spelled differently
  than the glossary entry.
* Remove some firstterm markups where no entry is in the glossary
  and adding one not useful.

Change-Id: Id7093a53f9d466db774b548749116288425af581

commit_message:
WIP: Argparse-based simple Solum CLI

* Uses argparse instead of the OpenStack Client as an option to consider
* Implements the create/delete app/assembly commands

Change-Id: I64e9606877574e6819f098874ec4542565af840b
Implements: blueprint solum-minimal-cli

commit_message:
Add test fail when Keystone not available

Implemented exception handling upon Keystone client
initialization. Added method that verifies if clients
have initialized and fails if they didn`t. Added
invocation of this method to setUp classes.

Change-Id: I9437b971cc54da144f12d0368b6181d004f82604
Closes-bug: 1267946

correct option name in class ceph

there is not osd_default_crush_rule option in ceph.conf, the correct
name is osd_pool_default_crush_rule.

Change-Id: Ice8ec6f0bdc1e8f1c5f143134eb0fdf108ceda1f

commit_message:
Part 1 of FloatingIP PTR record functionality

    This is part 1 - event handling in sink is Part 2 + Others.

    * Central methods update_floatingip, get_floatingip, list_floatingip
    * API according to
    * https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Designate/Blueprints/Reverse
    * Put network functionanlity into a pluggable api class (In case we want
    * more)

    blueprint floating-ip-ptrs

    Change-Id: Ic9194e5bcfc8d25126b9e84652144f58cddcccfe

Change-Id: Ib69f17ff8f2d888cf15f2cab7f46404cd201ae7e

commit_message:
Removed packages installed as dependencies by OVS plug-in agent

I removed packages installed as dependencies by the Open vSwitch
plug-in agent package on Ubuntu and Debian. For example, the
neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent package automatically installs
the openvswitch-switch package, so the instructions shouldn't
specifically call out installing the latter.

Also, on the controller node which doesn't need to run the OVS
plug-in agent but still needs to know about the configured plug-in,
I changed the neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent package to the
neutron-plugin-openvswitch package.

Change-Id: I13a50854149109a10155d0b6b05307a663563438
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1264184

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-01-13 21:21:06.000000000', 'message': "Removed package providing 'neutron-server' from network node

While fixing another bug, I noticed that the instructions for RHEL and
SUSE install a metapackage providing 'neutron-server', but do not
configure it to start on boot. In comparison, the Ubuntu instructions
install the specific package providing 'neutron-server' and
automatically configure it to start on boot.

I originally intended to patch this issue by providing instructions
for disabling 'neutron-server' in Upstart, but upon further
investigation, determined that 'neutron-server' does not need to run
on the network node, nor do any of the other packages
(neutron-l3-agent and neutron-dhcp-agent) depend on the neutron-server
package. So, this patch removes the neutron-server package from the
Ubuntu instructions and from the list of services to restart on all
distributions. I also removed the neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent
package from the Ubuntu instructions since we shouldn't cover specific
plug-ins in this section.

Change-Id: I5c08a56b37d8aef656826fc1b644efc799aa51a7
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1265833
"}]
commit_message:
Removed package providing 'neutron-server' from network node

While fixing another bug, I noticed that the instructions for RHEL and
SUSE install a metapackage providing 'neutron-server', but do not
configure it to start on boot. In comparison, the Ubuntu instructions
install the specific package providing 'neutron-server' and
automatically configure it to start on boot.

I originally intended to patch this issue by providing instructions
for disabling 'neutron-server' in Upstart, but upon further
investigation, determined that 'neutron-server' does not need to run
on the network node, nor do any of the other packages
(neutron-l3-agent and neutron-dhcp-agent) depend on the neutron-server
package. So, this patch removes the neutron-server package from the
Ubuntu instructions and from the list of services to restart on all
distributions. I also removed the neutron-plugin-openvswitch-agent
package from the Ubuntu instructions since we shouldn't cover specific
plug-ins in this section.

Change-Id: I5c08a56b37d8aef656826fc1b644efc799aa51a7
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1265833

commit_message:
strutils bool_from_string, allow specified default

In certain cases, we may want to return true by default, e.g see
the discussion in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/65725/, so provide
a "default" argument which can be used to override the existing default
False response.

Change-Id: I6c86b03125f263cf4843b4cf1addf9e9812f53a8

[{'created': '2014-01-13 14:58:05.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure Flask uses our JSON Encoder

Since the upgrade to Flask 0.10, we've not been using the correct
JSONEncoder. Up until today, we this was "not a problem", as
python-keystoneclient depended on simplejson, which provided the
necessary features.

python-keystoneclient 0.4.2 was released today, causing the issue
to finally surface.

Change-Id: Idc0e8f03608c80e097db2ea48b30f2bc0b8dbe5d
Closes-Bug: 1268607
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure Flask uses our JSON Encoder

Since the upgrade to Flask 0.10, we've not been using the correct
JSONEncoder. Up until today, we this was "not a problem", as
python-keystoneclient depended on simplejson, which provided the
necessary features.

python-keystoneclient 0.4.2 was released today, causing the issue
to finally surface.

Change-Id: Idc0e8f03608c80e097db2ea48b30f2bc0b8dbe5d
Closes-Bug: 1268607

commit_message:
Update neutron options for icehouse

Also fixed up some duplicate config options due to a bug in autohelp.py.
While working through duplication options, I believe I encountered some
that weren't being output, but I'd rather spend the time fixing the tool
than manually adding those.

Change-Id: I60eb035b97d354bc57168421facafd895ace2a10

commit_message:
Add CORS mention to object storage sec of confref

CORS was a feature added in Grizzly. This simple patch adds a new
section to the config reference, detailing what it is and the single
configuration option so far.

Change-Id: Ied2d5615e7b666370bc6d0dff136d305ba8cee62
Closes-Bug: 1107326

commit_message:
Add a fake ZooKeeper driver

This patch add a new driver which mimic a Kazoo client
without the need to use a real zookeeper server.

The dependency Zake (written by Joshua Harlow:harlowja@gmail.com)
has been added which provides the Kazoo API.

Change-Id: I53ca9ac972d6e2dca2f9e04b6187ee0545813e74

commit_message:
Add new modprobe-blacklist element.

This element can be used to provide a custom list
of modules via DIB_MODPROBE_BLACKLIST which
will be disabled via modprobe.d/blacklist.conf.

I'm using this to disable network adapters on the
Red Hat TripleO rack where the devices can't be
explicitly disabled via the BIOS.

Change-Id: I8a0a8ee05fa62628434d7f6422577dbf5cdd7a2e

Adds a new "package" type to origin-repositories. When the package type
is specified in an origin-repository-* file the package name and type
"package" need to be specified like so:

nova package

The existing map-packages mechanism can be used to map the specified

or not.

commit_message:
Add package support to source-repositories

Adds a new "package" type to source-repositories. When the package type
is specified in an origin-repository-* file the package name and type
"package" need to be specified like so:

nova package

The existing map-packages mechanism can be used to map the specified
package name to the actual distribution package names.  The
pre-configured package repositories on the image will be used to install
the packages during the install.d phase of the image build.

If the repo type is package, an environment.d hook script is updated
with an environment variable which is sourced by dib-run-parts. This is
so that other hooks, particularly in install.d, will know what repo type
was used and can make the correct decision about doing a source install
or not.

Change-Id: Ief4e524664cd32d2087aeb3b1766f05e017de91e

commit_message:
Use dynamic catalog for keystone on SUSE

Keystone uses dynamic catalog by default, which supports management
commands. Meanwhile, current static catalog default_catalog.templates
is lack of ceilometer endpoints.

This patch simply removes the catalog configure step to use default
setting.

Change-Id: Ie852c0dc4dc03b7120116dd25b10ee58a5d91e3e
Closes-Bug: #1267322
(cherry picked from commit b3ae3222b34f7282f875658387228de650f81d77)

commit_message:
Allow passing extra args to JobExecutionsManager.create()

Java job types require additional parameters beyond cluster_id and
configs.  Add an optional dictionary and an update call to allow
for additional key/value settings.

Closes-Bug: #1268695

Change-Id: I995e648a939063170d1a2ac7040493351fb67f74

Keystone uses dynamic catalog by default, which supports management
commands. Meanwhile, current static catalog default_catalog.templates
is lack of ceilometer endpoints.

This patch simply removes the catalog configure step to use default
setting.

Change-Id: Ie852c0dc4dc03b7120116dd25b10ee58a5d91e3e
Closes-Bug: #1267322
'}]
commit_message:
Use dynamic catalog for keystone on SUSE

Keystone uses dynamic catalog by default, which supports management
commands. Meanwhile, current static catalog default_catalog.templates
is lack of ceilometer endpoints.

This patch simply removes the catalog configure step to use default
setting.

Change-Id: Ie852c0dc4dc03b7120116dd25b10ee58a5d91e3e
Closes-Bug: #1267322

commit_message:
Add a wait condition to undercloud stack

Using of Heat wait conditions allows us to reliably reason when a
stack creation is complete (as the completion handle is triggered
when os-refresh-config completes).

Change-Id: I89725143532177a0b4aea23c1c31bc7737da0896

commit_message:
Setup for openstack-doc-tools

Add files to allow us gating via:
tox -e checkbuild
tox -e checkniceness
etc

Add .gitignore to ignore files used by gating.

Add initial README file to document this

Change-Id: I821e1848bb364f7514c54e87f5d29d4254b9e025

I think it should be extracted in separate fence_agent, nailgun agent should just send current state of node, without some additional actions and should know nothing about fencing and so on. Also what if we want to change period of running fencing checkings and want to keep period of agent as it was?

Also we already have a transport (mcollective) and orchestrator where we can check and initiate fencting of nodes.

And take a look at https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-astute how we keep dependencies requirements there."}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2014-01-10 13:09:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2014-01-10 13:10:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add check_and_fence method and tests for nailgun agent:NodeAgent

To run unit tests use:
rspec ./bin/agent_spec.rb --color --format documentation

Make sure you have:
ruby 1.9.3p429 / 1.8.7p371
rspec 2.14.7
---------------------
httpclient (2.3.4.1)
json (1.8.1)
logger (1.2.8)
ohai (6.20.0)
rethtool (0.0.3)

Implements: blueprint fencing-in-nailgun-agent

Change-Id: Ic7d9d38a65514a89aa1581109757fb1ed8a6702c
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bogdando@mail.ru>
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Prevent caller from specifying id during PciDevice.create()

The patch is to remove id when it was set before creating a PCI device
in objects.

Related to blueprint icehouse-objects.

Change-Id: Idd6d40e88f7251307504c945453281656eebb073

commit_message:
Validate further XML files

Do simple XML validation of .xsd, .xsl, .xjb files - just for well-formed XML,
no schema validation yet.

Fix a bug introduced with version 0.2 that we did not use a schema
for .wadl files. Testing this, there were too many errors with the RelaxNG
validation, so use XMLSchema as recommend by David Cramer.

Added XMLSchema files for local parsing.

Change-Id: I589f00a2e3dc46b6b3ba5e965fa9d4eba6d1a295

commit_message:
Only add ceilometer user to nova group if using compute agent

When using ceilometer outside of the compute context (ex: with the
swift middleware), puppet-ceilometer attempts to add the user to
the nova group which does not (and probably should not) exist on
the swift nodes.

Change-Id: I6cc68152325a967c024ce611f92a90ce0afba8cc

commit_message:
Update Obj-auditor to support multiple storage policies

objects will be stored in directories like 'objects', 'objects-1',
'objects-2'..., so simply update obj-auditor to audit these data
also.
