subject: Allow user creating with fields have ":" or "-"
messages:
[{'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2014-01-08 08:41:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-01-08 15:41:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Mind adding a quick test case to validate the new behavior?

Thanks!

-jay"}, {'account_id': 220, 'date': '2014-01-08 18:59:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

We should not allow  ":"  "-" is fine.

In xml ":" is used as XML name space delimiter. If you allow ":" in field name then in xml you will have ":". I don't think any parser will recognize this.

e.g 
Assume field name is    my:xyz, then in xml it will transform to

  my:xmz in case of default namespace prefix and
  prefix:my:xyx in case of named prefix.


None of the openstack projects care about xml support  but in case if they plan to support it, it is better to not have  ":"'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2014-01-14 07:07:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

abandon'}]

commit_message:
Allow user creating with fields have ":" or "-"

If we define custom fields which ":" or "-", when creating user,keystone
will convert ":" and "-" to "_". It should not be so.

Change-Id: If0467421d5b18a9cdc2c88fecfb1befd23307e5f
Closes-bug: #1241218

commit_message:
Add API schema for v3 admin_actions API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistency for
whole of Nova APIs.

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-validation-fw

Change-Id: Id58e0bd2e07c634e1649a41b8333e3657d7e08cf

commit_message:
Fix flavor extra_spec usages

"nova-manage" command is deprecated and "nova flavor-key" can set
flavor extra_spec instead. This patch changes the usage to show
"nova flavor-key".
In addition, "nova flavor-set" command does not exist.
This patch fixes it with "nova flavor-key" command.

Change-Id: If41899cf0af463ccc2db5127d53398f73e3a26a7

commit_message:
Simple Certificate Extension

Implement the Simple Certificate Extension for retrieving the signing
certificates from a server.

This extension brings in a simple Pecan extension router that allows new
extensions to be developed with Pecan/wSME. The extension and the router
are grouped because the extension is about the simplest test of the
router as possible.

Change-Id: I7811480f2e83f10ee26e1d9fe60fb52834d07d19
Closes-Bug: #1259011

Probably 'timestamp' could be marked as deprecated parameter and then the duplication could be removed in a later version of the API."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-01-06 21:34:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi lizheming,

Apologies, I didn't realize that you'd already submitted a patch for this when I proposed:

  https://review.openstack.org/65118

The reason being that the bug in launchpad was not auto-updated with details of your gerrit proposal, as your commit message didn't include a reference to the bug ID in a form that the gerrit/LP hook understands (e.g. "Fixes bug 1262335").

In any case, this patch is not going to fly without tests. I've included tests in my patch, which you can either copy or else just abandon this patch in favour of the one with test coverage.

Also, in terms of the backward compatibility and the pre-existing timestamp field. I'm not sure this is even an issue TBH, as this field would not ever have previously been set, because the corresponding attribute did not exist on the Resource model. So in that case, there can't have been any existing clients that depended on the timestamp attribute being set in the API response to GET /v2/resources. Hence I'm inclined to think we could just disregard this field.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-01-14 06:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned

commit_message:
Resource api lack of first&last sample timestamps

The first & last sample timestamps for any meter
associated with a resource are calculated when
we retrieve the Resource models from the storage
driver,but mismatch between the Resource model and
the Resource representation returned by the API.

Change-Id: I5a36558e85d8799bab6deb38a1774e8d790157a5
Closes-Bug: #1262335

commit_message:
Add domain boundaries to user/group/project lists

With respect to the domain concept, the access of a user should be
contained inside the scoped project or domain. This is a preliminary
support of domain in the three listing features.

Implements: blueprint Domain-Level Trusts
Change-Id: Ifa14c7a22a79d911fcc783eae35696e959e54413
Signed-off-by: Bo Tang <btang@cs.utsa.edu>

commit_message:
Fixed a problem in iSCSI multipath

Multipathing during copy image to volume and copy volume to image
operations doesn't work properly if there are different targets
associated with different portals for a mulitpath device.

Change-Id: I21ac6715b470b148340cc231b994ffd0fbe7c9bd
Closes-Bug: #1266048

associated with different portals for a mulitpath device.

commit_message:
REST API for software config/deployment

This REST API creates two new base paths to manage config and deployment
entities:
* /{tenant_id}/software_configs
* /{tenant_id}/software_deployments

This is a POC change which currently lacks tests.

partial blueprint: hot-software-config-rest
Change-Id: I72259a454713ed1bfe423ba10e35a6f1e6a0dbee

[{'created': '2014-01-06 08:43:39.000000000', 'message': "check hypervisor's trust level instead compute for TrustedFilter

The TrustedFilter uses host_state.host as the name that will be checked
against the remote attestation service.

This works for the KVM case because the compute node and the hypervisor
are the same; however we must be checking host_state.nodename which is
the hostname for the hypervisor which will be registered with the
attestation server.

commit_message:
check hypervisor's trust level instead compute for TrustedFilter

The TrustedFilter uses host_state.host as the name that will be checked
against the remote attestation service.

This works for the KVM case because the compute node and the hypervisor
are the same; however we must be checking host_state.nodename which is
the hostname for the hypervisor which will be registered with the
attestation server.

Change-Id: I6065b9400dd329d37a1ff90179423f259d53713c
Closes-bug: #1223452

commit_message:
Added profiler notification plugin

This plugin collects profiler messages into ceilometer.
Currently it listens on 2 exchanges: nova + separate rally exchange.
Later all messages should only be sent to rally exchange.

Implements blueprint profiler-rpc-collector

Change-Id: Iac7c68066164dfd010e1485515f0d813a77c959e

1. This adds python-openstack client as dependency.
2. This copies and modifies shell.py and clientmanager.py.

TODO:

The client should be modified to accept token so that token can be passed to the
client as it is done in other clients. Now in shell.py we are relying to token
from auth plugin set on http client.

Change-Id: Ib191a17b0da80049be93cd2da7d24412da8fcb3c
'}]
commit_message:
WIP: Shell based on python-openstack client.

1. This adds python-openstack client as dependency.
2. This copies and modifies shell.py and clientmanager.py.

TODO:

The client should be modified to accept token so that token can be passed to the
client as it is done in other clients. Now in shell.py we are relying to token
from auth plugin set on http client.

Change-Id: Ib191a17b0da80049be93cd2da7d24412da8fcb3c

This change allows NetBeans to show the project source files in the

commit_message:
Make assertQueryStringIs usage simpler

As requested in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/65728/, this "fixes"
assertQueryStringIs so it takes a query string, rather than a dict
of lists, which is a less convenient format in many tests.

Change-Id: Ib4c49ba71f7e12bb5bcb4dfde77974f3418c7854

Bind enforcement should be pluggable. I may even go as far as saying it needs to be its own middleware."}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-10-08 01:33:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

So i don't disagree that we should have pluggable binding support. But i see it being quite a while before anyone needs more than x509 and kerberos and from the auth_token middleware side we don't really have support for anything like this yet. 

Regarding being middleware, that is certainly an option, i don't necessarily think it's a good idea, it isn't middleware server side (though i see it could be) and we don't really have precedent for adding additional middleware which is essentially auth_token related. 

I'm interested in the discussion here though."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-15 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
Verify token binding in auth_token middleware

The server side has had token bind checking implemented for a while. Now
that it is possible to generate bound tokens auth_token middleware
should be capable of verifying them.

Change-Id: I4f9c5855ab3102333b0738864c506e2501bf9c7e

I'll fix that up too."}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2013-12-19 03:43:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 1216, 'date': '2013-12-19 03:44:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Okay, I made those changes, including the fallback key2.

Also, I added /info support (that's a new and cool feature I forgot was just added to master).

I'm unclear how to auto-upgrade folks' current X-Container-Sync-To values and I'm leery of trying to do that.

I did add an option, allow_full_urls, which if set false will disallow any new full urls to be set on the X-Container-Sync-To header, allowing only realm specifications.

Upgrading existing values in a cluster will have to be done manually if someone wants to convert from old-style container sync to the new style. Probably best to:

  * Install the new-style with allow_full_urls = false, which keeps anyone from making new container sync full url endpoints and forcing new settings to be new-style only.
  * Then, run a script to find all the containers with the old-style values and contact the owners to get them updated. A script such as this: https://gist.github.com/gholt/8034056
  * Finally, remove the old-style allow_sync_hosts conf setting."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-19 04:25:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-08 09:25:24.000000000', 'message': 'First draft of new container sync configuration

Still a work-in-progress, but submitted in case any want to give
early feedback. This should mosty be "code complete", but needs tests
for all the new stuff. Of course, it's only pre-review code complete.

Summary of the new configuration option:

The cluster operators create a container_sync_realms.conf for their
cluster and copy this out to all their proxy and container servers.
This file specifies the available container sync "realms".

A container sync realm is a group of clusters with a shared key that
have agreed to provide container syncing to one another.

The end user can then set the X-Container-Sync-To value on a
container to //realm/cluster/account/container instead of the
previously required URL.

The allowed hosts list is not used with this configuration and
instead every container sync request sent is signed using the realm
key and user key.

This offers better security as source hosts can be faked much more
easily than faking per request signatures. Replaying signed requests,
assuming it could easily be done, shouldn't be an issue as the
X-Timestamp is part of the signature and so would just short-circuit
as already current or as superceded.

This also makes configuration easier for the end user, especially
with difficult networking situations where a different host might
need to be used for the container sync daemon since it's connecting
from within a cluster. With this new configuration option, the end
user just specifies the realm and cluster names and that is resolved
to the proper endpoint configured by the operator. If the operator
changes their configuration (key or endpoint), the end user does not
need to change theirs.

Change-Id: Ie1704990b66d0434e4991e26ed1da8b08cb05a37

commit_message:
New container sync configuration option

Summary of the new configuration option:

The cluster operators add the container_sync middleware to their
proxy pipeline and create a container-sync-realms.conf for their
cluster and copy this out to all their proxy and container servers.
This file specifies the available container sync "realms".

A container sync realm is a group of clusters with a shared key that
have agreed to provide container syncing to one another.

The end user can then set the X-Container-Sync-To value on a
container to //realm/cluster/account/container instead of the
previously required URL.

The allowed hosts list is not used with this configuration and
instead every container sync request sent is signed using the realm
key and user key.

This offers better security as source hosts can be faked much more
easily than faking per request signatures. Replaying signed requests,
assuming it could easily be done, shouldn't be an issue as the
X-Timestamp is part of the signature and so would just short-circuit
as already current or as superceded.

This also makes configuration easier for the end user, especially
with difficult networking situations where a different host might
need to be used for the container sync daemon since it's connecting
from within a cluster. With this new configuration option, the end
user just specifies the realm and cluster names and that is resolved
to the proper endpoint configured by the operator. If the operator
changes their configuration (key or endpoint), the end user does not
need to change theirs.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ie1704990b66d0434e4991e26ed1da8b08cb05a37

commit_message:
Fix showing events on swift.

We don't need to auth again since we already have a valid preauthurl and
preauthtoken already.

Change-Id: Ic48b1bfccaef8f47b46fffb5a014a05b0ce37a9c
Closes-Bug: 1263799

commit_message:
libvirt, fix test tpool_execute_calls_libvirt

An exception raised by mock for expected method is obscured
by the "catch Exception" on libvirt/driver.py#643.

This patch updates the test to be more coherent with the code.

Change-Id: I629634395d11432f9d7e4fbe330b864490fa1801

commit_message:
Implements Nova FloatingIP resources

    https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/nova-networking-floatingip

This code aims to add support OS::Nova::FloatingIP
and OS::Nova::FloatingIPAssociation in Heat.

Change-Id: I678f8a099b97c0fb46bf1056203fc9bafe3032aa
Implements: blueprint nova-networking-floatingip

commit_message:
Allow passed-in TE_DATAFILE environments.

Adding --existing-environment when invoking devtest.sh will now skip
setting up the test environment. This is useful for either folk
running with baremetal, or TripleO-CI which is using externally
provisioned VMs.

Change-Id: Iea34f22e91d6476614d027d6188037ee541277cd

commit_message:
Create and use a JSON testenvironment file.

This is the format that TripleO-CI will be passing test environments
through to devtest, so by using it ourselves we avoid special casing
things quite so much.

Using a JSON testenvironment file also permits partially fixing a
FIXME in devtest.sh to stop sourcing some of the devtest scripts.

Change-Id: Ic3b0b482f411427ac8411591edc793e32401310f

commit_message:
No longer export DEPLOY_IMAGE_ELEMENT

While working towards no longer sourcing the children scripts to remove
some of the sharp edges of devtest, ramdisk can be overridden by the
parent, so DEPLOY_IMAGE_ELEMENT no longer needs to be exported.

Change-Id: Iba7f45f525c85fd3203d3aa0bd97a426ad51ce7f

commit_message:
Populate devtest_variables from devtest_setup.

Shift great hunks from devtest_setup (all of the things like exporting
variables) into devtest_variables. This allows developers to just
source devtest_variables.sh into their environment to run the other
scripts that depend on the variables existing in the environment.

Change-Id: Idd412616a547c5af1c13ead8bcdc911a26c5527b

commit_message:
Start to split devtest_setup out more.

The goal of this effort is to be able to not create VM's during
devtest, so that CI can work with it's predefined environments.
Separately, for folk doing devtest steps by hand, having a safe thing
we can source, separate from the active script that installs packages
etc, seems like a good idea. Thus _testenv and _variables. Of course,
keeping the narrative intact is tricky too - so this patch just sets
up the layout, allowing me and StevenK to work in parallel on the
splitout.

The new TE_DATAFILE variable identifies the test environment file we
will write (in this case) or use (in the TOCI case).

Change-Id: I2cff0bfd09dcaff1e118f519b8d81a74496c6568

commit_message:
Fixes bug 1264418 for Tempest Nova

Changes assertEqual to assertTrue with issubset, that the expected
metadata key/value is a subset of actual metadata from resource,
allowing third-party driver to write metadata for its own purpose.

Fixes: bug #1264418
Change-Id: I653b66da67d5cd6929384309eb757d2b47134084

Patch set 10 turns the rate limiting for SLOs off by default, as well as fixes a nasty bug found by dfg where a range GET that started exactly on a segment boundary would fail due to a garden-variety off-by-one error.

The rate limiting defaults to off because the old rate limiting didn't actually affect SLOs; there was an explicit check in there to only do rate limiting for DLOs. It's nice to have, though, so I left it in. This does mean that deployers don't need to take any special action on upgrade, which is always nice."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-07 01:39:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Doesn't seem to work

First, I would like to say I really like this work, as it, along with the anticipated DLO work, will allow me to continue work on proxy-server changes to support multiple storage backends (today the protocol from proxy to backend server is fixed, and I'd like to propose a way to adjust that, along with by-passing using "lo" interface for in-host transactions).

That said, one of the highlights from the commit message is that the COPY operation is a sort of a hack. While that description is debatable, it seems that the unit tests do not cover that code path. Would it be possible to get coverage for that operation? Given that the unit tests appear to be completely re-written, it might be worth our time to ensure this behavior.

And I'd like to see near 100% coverage of the slo middleware module, given from the looks of it, it is fairly attainable with a couple more tests.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-16 19:31:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-16 19:32:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-15 23:09:48.000000000', 'message': 'Move all SLO functionality to middleware

This way, with zero additional effort, SLO will support any future
enhancements made to object storage and retrieval, such as:
 * automatic retry of GETs on broken connection (proxy <-> backend)
 * storage policies
 * erasure-coded object segments

This also lets SLOs work with other sorts of hypothetical third-party
middleware, for example object compression or encryption.

NOTE TO DEPLOYERS: You'll need to copy the "rate_limit_after_segment"
and "rate_limit_segments_per_sec" from the proxy server's
configuration stanza ("app:proxy-server") to the SLO middleware's
configuration stanza. Otherwise, those settings will revert to
default. (SLO's defaults are the same as the proxy's defaults, so if
you haven't changed those settings, no action needs to be taken.)

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ic11662eb5c7176fbf422a6fc87a569928d6f85a1
'}, {'created': '2013-11-20 03:18:20.000000000', 'message': 'Move all SLO functionality to middleware

This way, with zero additional effort, SLO will support any future

This also lets SLOs work with other sorts of hypothetical third-party
middleware, for example object compression or encryption.

Getting COPY to work here is sort of a hack; the proxy's object
controller now checks for "swift.copy_response_hook" in the request's
environment and feeds the GET response (the source of the new object's
data) through it. This lets a COPY of a SLO manifest actually combine
the segments instead of merely copying the manifest document.

'}, {'created': '2013-12-02 23:59:44.000000000', 'message': 'Move all SLO functionality to middleware

This way, with zero additional effort, SLO will support any future
enhancements made to object storage and retrieval, such as:
 * automatic retry of GETs on broken connection (proxy <-> backend)
 * storage policies
 * erasure-coded object segments

This also lets SLOs work with other sorts of hypothetical third-party
middleware, for example object compression or encryption.

Getting COPY to work here is sort of a hack; the proxy's object
controller now checks for "swift.copy_response_hook" in the request's
environment and feeds the GET response (the source of the new object's
data) through it. This lets a COPY of a SLO manifest actually combine
the segments instead of merely copying the manifest document.

Updated ObjectController to expect a response's app_iter to be an
iterable, not just an iterator. (PEP 333 says "When called by the
server, the application object must return an iterable yielding zero
or more strings." ObjectController was just being too strict.) This
way, SLO can re-use the same response-generation logic for GET and
COPY requests.

NOTE TO DEPLOYERS: You'll need to copy the "rate_limit_after_segment"
and "rate_limit_segments_per_sec" from the proxy server's
configuration stanza ("app:proxy-server") to the SLO middleware's
configuration stanza. Otherwise, those settings will revert to
default. (SLO's defaults are the same as the proxy's defaults, so if
you haven't changed those settings, no action needs to be taken.)

'}, {'created': '2013-12-06 23:25:34.000000000', 'message': 'Move all SLO functionality to middleware

This way, with zero additional effort, SLO will support any future
enhancements made to object storage and retrieval, such as:
 * automatic retry of GETs on broken connection (proxy <-> backend)
 * storage policies
 * erasure-coded object segments

This also lets SLOs work with other sorts of hypothetical third-party
middleware, for example object compression or encryption.

Getting COPY to work here is sort of a hack; the proxy's object
controller now checks for "swift.copy_response_hook" in the request's
environment and feeds the GET response (the source of the new object's
data) through it. This lets a COPY of a SLO manifest actually combine
the segments instead of merely copying the manifest document.

Updated ObjectController to expect a response's app_iter to be an
iterable, not just an iterator. (PEP 333 says "When called by the
server, the application object must return an iterable yielding zero
or more strings." ObjectController was just being too strict.) This
way, SLO can re-use the same response-generation logic for GET and
COPY requests.

Added a (sort of hokey) mechanism to allow middlewares to close
incompletely-consumed app iterators without triggering a warning. SLO
does this when it realizes it's performed a ranged GET on a manifest;
it closes the iterable, removes the range, and retries the
request. Without this change, the proxy logs would get 'Client
disconnected on read' in them.

NOTE TO DEPLOYERS: You'll need to copy the "rate_limit_after_segment"
and "rate_limit_segments_per_sec" from the proxy server's
configuration stanza ("app:proxy-server") to the SLO middleware's
configuration stanza. Otherwise, those settings will revert to
default. (SLO's defaults are the same as the proxy's defaults, so if
you haven't changed those settings, no action needs to be taken.)

environment and feeds the GET response (the source of the new object's
data) through it. This lets a COPY of a SLO manifest actually combine
the segments instead of merely copying the manifest document.

Updated ObjectController to expect a response's app_iter to be an
iterable, not just an iterator. (PEP 333 says "When called by the
server, the application object must return an iterable yielding zero
or more strings." ObjectController was just being too strict.) This
way, SLO can re-use the same response-generation logic for GET and
COPY requests.

Added a (sort of hokey) mechanism to allow middlewares to close
incompletely-consumed app iterators without triggering a warning. SLO
does this when it realizes it's performed a ranged GET on a manifest;
it closes the iterable, removes the range, and retries the
request. Without this change, the proxy logs would get 'Client
disconnected on read' in them.

DocImpact

commit_message:
Move all SLO functionality to middleware

This way, with zero additional effort, SLO will support enhancements
to object storage and retrieval, such as:
 * automatic resume of GETs on broken connection (today)
 * storage policies (in the near future)
 * erasure-coded object segments (in the far future)

This also lets SLOs work with other sorts of hypothetical third-party
middleware, for example object compression or encryption.

Getting COPY to work here is sort of a hack; the proxy's object
controller now checks for "swift.copy_response_hook" in the request's
environment and feeds the GET response (the source of the new object's
data) through it. This lets a COPY of a SLO manifest actually combine
the segments instead of merely copying the manifest document.

Updated ObjectController to expect a response's app_iter to be an
iterable, not just an iterator. (PEP 333 says "When called by the
server, the application object must return an iterable yielding zero
or more strings." ObjectController was just being too strict.) This
way, SLO can re-use the same response-generation logic for GET and
COPY requests.

Added a (sort of hokey) mechanism to allow middlewares to close
incompletely-consumed app iterators without triggering a warning. SLO
does this when it realizes it's performed a ranged GET on a manifest;
it closes the iterable, removes the range, and retries the
request. Without this change, the proxy logs would get 'Client
disconnected on read' in them.

DocImpact

blueprint multi-ring-large-objects

Change-Id: Ic11662eb5c7176fbf422a6fc87a569928d6f85a1

output and causes pdb prompt to quit.

Tips for how to run testr with debug are provided here:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Testr#Debugging_.28pdb.29_Tests

you can do a command like

 tox -e debug test_auth_token_middleware

and when it hits your breakpoint you'll get the debug prompt.

"}]
commit_message:
Debug env for tox

Running a test with pdb was difficult because testr captures
output and causes pdb prompt to quit.

Tips for how to run testr with debug are provided here:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Testr#Debugging_.28pdb.29_Tests

This change puts these commands into a debug env in tox.ini so
you can do a command like

 tox -e debug test_auth_token_middleware

or, for more granularity:
 tox -e debug keystone.tests.test_sql_migrate_extensions.EndpointFilterExtension
 tox -e debug keystone.tests.test_sql_migrate_extensions.EndpointFilterExtension.test_downgrade

and when it hits your breakpoint you'll get the debug prompt.

This same change was made to keystone in commit c8302509 .

Change-Id: I2b5dc81f4652dc89ecbcc7c785245a81cf77a1ca

commit_message:
Documentation cleanup

Several warnings and errors were reported when building
documentation. This makes it difficult for developers to
validate that new changes to don't have problems.

Most of the warnings and errors are fixed with this change.

Change-Id: Ifb9edffce66dde27fbe72bb1ce1b997b041786ae

commit_message:
Convert Token KVS backend to new KeyValueStore Impl

This patchset converts the current token KVS backend to the new
dogpile.cache based KeyValueStore implementation.  The changeset
provides the same public interface as the previous KVS driver but
drastically reworks the internal mechanisms to be more similar to
the memcache based driver so that direct access to the in-mem db
is not required to effectively use the KeyValueStore.

KVS token backend is not deprecated anymore. However, it is still
inadvisable to use the basic-inmemory KVS backend for anything
outside of testing.

DocImpact

bp: dogpile-kvs-backends
Change-Id: Ib278636d4ffa3f7152287a48d02be598c50f698a

[{'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-12-13 19:13:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-12-13 19:20:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(no comment on the proposed code itself, just a meta comment about it)

One important note is that middleware is an implementation detail, not a "feature flag" thing. That is, a configurable feature may be implemented in the app, and a required feature could be implemented in middleware.

So that being said, if a feature is or isn't implemented in middleware in Swift shouldn't make much difference here. What is important is that some features may be turned on and off, and you have a mechanism for configuring that in tests. I think that's a great thing.

In the Swift 1.11 release (released yesterday), we have an official mechanism for querying a Swift cluster to see what's enabled. The available docs are at http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/misc.html#discoverability (yes I'd like to see them get better). If there are things that aren't currently exposed via /info, I'd love your help to get them added.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-13 20:30:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

@Joe
Thanks for the confirmation. The scope of this patch is to just convert the existing config options for discoverable optional swift api features to be a single list opt. I'm sure there are places where we need to add checks for optional features before running the test. That is the next step, and patches are welcome to do that on top of this commit. I've got limited bandwidth, so I'll get to it eventually.

As a quick aside if there is an optional feature that isn't discoverable that should still be a separate option. This distinction is a bit more straightforward on some of the other projects that have extensions. The separation is a bit more strained on swift and keystone which is why I went with discoverability (originally middleware) as the separating factor. This change is just to prevent the set of config options from exploding. For example, in the nova case there are ~80 extensions which would mean 80 new config options for each one. If you have a different idea for a distinction or some other config structure around swift that would work better I really would appreciate it as I'm fairly unfamiliar with both the swift api and configurations."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-12-17 22:27:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-17 23:14:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Add a discoverable_apis option for swift

This commit adds a new list option for the object-storage-feature-enabled
config group, discoverable_apis, which lists out which Swift discoverable
optional apis are expected to be enabled on the swift server. It also
converts the pre-existing single boolean options for these types of
features to use the new list option. This option is used in the same
manner as the extensions list options for the other services. However,
since swift doesn't have the same concept of extensions as some of the
other OpenStack projects optional discoverable apis (which are often
but not always tied with middleware) were used instead. If an optional
api being enabled isn't discoverable from an external api call then
that should have a separate config option in the

Add Marconi to Tempest config

This patch adds queuing to tempest config, provided queuing is
available in devstack.

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.iteritems and six.string_types

six.iteritems() replaces dictionary.iteritems() on Python 2 and
dictionary.items() on Python 3.

six.string_types replaces basestring() in Python 2 and str
in Python 3.

Change-Id: Ia18510d167df35caec83626718010228e2140bc0

commit_message:
Add lib{xml2,xslt1}-dev to Debian dependencies

libxml2-dev and libxslt1-dev are required for devtest, so
install-dependencies should install them for Debian.

commit_message:
Update spec_helper to include 'chefspec/berkshelf'

This minor change allows you to run rspec outside of strainer while
still having cookbook dependencies automatically handled by berkshelf
(which also means you can run individual chefspec tests).

Note that this change does marginally increase the time it takes to run
a strainer test.

A similar change was recently accepted in the openstack-compute
cookbook.

Change-Id: I45adc06dae0805bd401f7c16b703b2717e1ac46d

commit_message:
Implement consistent hashing of nodes to conductors

Implement the consistent hashing of nodes to conductors.

Implement automatic routing of RPC messages from the API tier to the
conductor tier, by using the consistent hash ring.

Improves _sync_power_states to only check the nodes mapped to that
particular conductor.

Add a stub for a rebalance method which can trigger certain actions by a
conductor when a node is mapped to it by changes in the hash
distribution.

blueprint instance-mapping-by-consistent-hash

Change-Id: Ib74a8ded49e4a85964c46d4a445ff0a2df39862a

commit_message:
Ensure ML2 plugin package is installed

Some platforms have a package for ML2 plugin.

This change makes sure is it installed for those platforms when
ML2 plugin is used and configured.

Change-Id: I24c8eb7d17a462b63d2023027c90da7f876f7503
Closes-bug: #1264205
(cherry picked from commit b68158470abaeeb4431fc683994f2b7f8c71ea38)

commit_message:
Fix icmp security group rule creation

Previously invalid icmp rules were created which lead to incorrect
duplicate detection. When valid rules are created duplicates are
correctly detected so rally does not attempt to crate the same rule
twice.

Change-Id: Ia1262f3595b679e267ff1a9cb7cfe9f31e02c2b8
Closes-Bug: #1268687

commit_message:
Fix volume metadata validation of identical to request

This change is for fixing bug 1264418 tempest cases.
During the creating volume process, driver can add specified
data to "metadata", but some tempest cases avoid to do so.
Use assertDictContainsSubset instead of assertEqual to check
the metadata. Also verified this changeset works.

Modified per Giulio's comment:
Use testtool.matcher#ContainsAll to assert if the dict contains
the sub dict.

Change-Id: Ief92b60d39acbde97f620b1a9ab943a13022d839
Partial-Bug: 1264418

commit_message:
rubocop compliance

all cops now pass except for the following
(which are silenced in .rubocop.yml )

* LineLength, MethodLength: not sure if we care about these
* WordArray: I prefer [] vs %w{} for readability.

Change-Id: I92996b5db9f292e9ba93c7619ca727ffa92ddd71

Conflicts:
	metadata.rb
	recipes/common.rb
	recipes/openvswitch.rb
	spec/openvswitch_spec.rb

Change-Id: Ia68a9b27e50f6de8fac4c74bc34dfcc201857fb3

commit_message:
Add /var/cache/swift to the list of directories that must be owned by swift.

/var/cache/swift must be writeable by the user swift. python-swift in ubuntu
grizzly packages does not create /var/cache/swift with the proper permissions.
This was fixed and released for havana packages.

Related-Bug: #1234657
Change-Id: I27e4835b4d1833c493347cfcc51f4b9489c29d63

commit_message:
Configure security group when using ML2 plugin

Since the ML2 plugin can concurrently support different L2 agents (or
other mechanisms) with different configurations, Neutron developpers recommend
setting firewall_driver flag in ml2 configuration.

Change-Id: I62d0d1b2aac88a11e5f3e80e98953c71cfc98629
Closes-bug: #1262678
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit 59cf3eb0a22c220509ec80c345bbf064f85374ad)

commit_message:
Clarified example architectures

I clarified the example architectures section to cover the two primary
architectures assumed throughout the installation guide. This patch
fixes the immediate issue of operators not understanding assumptions
made by the guide. A future patch for this bug will include improved
text and diagrams based on example architectures chosen for Icehouse.

Change-Id: I2529f7a4a66c0e7442d675f65909579aba3a0ad6
backport: havana
Partial-Bug: #1263719
(cherry picked from commit 420ed1d2198af31abe73d36cbb5a14ab72f6e3bb)
